{"title_page": "Baghuwar, Madhya Pradesh", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Baghuwar''' or Baghuvar is also pronounced as (Devanagari: \u092c\u0918\u0941\u0935\u093e\u0930) is a village located in the Kareli block of Narsinghpur district in the state of Madhya Pradesh of India. The village falls under the division of Jabalpur and positioned at a  distance of 201 km from the state capital of Bhopal.\n\n==In The News==\nIt is the only village in India that has an existence since independence and that too witho<ref>{{cite web |title=Demographic |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/23/2335_PART_A_DCHB_NARSIMHAPUR.pdf |website=censusindia.gov.in}}</ref>ut a sarpanch. Each & every house in the village has its common toilet complex that is used for social gatherings. The sewage lines are also there in the village. In order to cook food and light up the village, the produced gas is used.<ref>{{cite web |title=15 Inspiring Indian Villages That Are Showing the Way Forward |url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/85354/inspiring-indian-villages-sustainable-development/ |website=thebetterindia.com}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nThe village with its population of 2400 transformed itself without taking the help of others at least 7 years before the launch of the Swachh Bharat campaign by Prime Minister Narendra Modi. The villagers claim Baghuvar became ODF in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=This village in Madhya Pradesh imbibed Bapu\u2019s teachings, became ODF in 2004 - bhopal |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/this-village-in-madhya-pradesh-imbibed-bapu-s-teachings-became-odf-in-2004/story-nqScF7qKc6rgHaPO5k7rpL.html |website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref>\n==Demographic==\nThe Baghwar/Baghwar Census Location Code Number of 2001 is 04812000 and Census Location Code Number of 2011 is 491371. The total area of the village is 906.7 hectares in which total population was 1946 in which number of households were 465.\n\n==Agriculture==\nThe black soil is found in the village which is suited for any kind of cultivation. Rabi and Kharif are the two seasons of cultivation here.\n\n==Geography==\nThe latitude 23.24 and longitude 77.4 are the geocoordinate of the Baghuwar. The local language is Hindi which is used for communication.The Pincode of the village is 487221 & the telephone code is 07793. <ref>{{cite web |title=Geography |url=https://www.indiapost.gov.in/VAS/Pages/LocatePostOffices.aspx?Pin=hIMLHC4Jl9M= |website=indiapost.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding Villages==\nThe villages near are - \n* Mohad\n* Amheta\n* Khiriya\n* Biner\n* Karoda\n* Bamhori\n* Amgaon\n* Barodiya\n* Tinsara\n* Simariya Khurd\n* Pipariya\n==References==\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Baghuwar''' or Baghuvar is also pronounced as (Devanagari: \u092c\u0918\u0941\u0935\u093e\u0930) is a village located in the Kareli block of Narsinghpur district in the state of Madhya Pradesh of India. The village falls under the division of Jabalpur and positioned at a  distance of 201 km from the state capital of Bhopal.\n\n==In The News==\nIt is the only village in India that has an existence since independence and that too witho<ref>{{cite web |title=Demographic |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/23/2335_PART_A_DCHB_NARSIMHAPUR.pdf |website=censusindia.gov.in}}</ref>ut a sarpanch. Each & every house in the village has its common toilet complex that is used for social gatherings. The sewage lines are also there in the village. In order to cook food and light up the village, the produced gas is used.<ref>{{cite web |title=15 Inspiring Indian Villages That Are Showing the Way Forward |url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/85354/inspiring-indian-villages-sustainable-development/ |website=thebetterindia.com}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nThe village with its population of 2400 transformed itself without taking the help of others at least 7 years before the launch of the Swachh Bharat campaign by Prime Minister Narendra Modi. The villagers claim Baghuvar became ODF in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=This village in Madhya Pradesh imbibed Bapu\u2019s teachings, became ODF in 2004 - bhopal |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/this-village-in-madhya-pradesh-imbibed-bapu-s-teachings-became-odf-in-2004/story-nqScF7qKc6rgHaPO5k7rpL.html |website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref>\n==Demographic==\nThe Baghwar/Baghwar Census Location Code Number of 2001 is 04812000 and Census Location Code Number of 2011 is 491371. The total area of the village is 906.7 hectares in which total population was 1946 in which number of households were 465.\n\n==Agriculture==\nThe black soil is found in the village which is suited for any kind of cultivation. Rabi and Kharif are the two seasons of cultivation here.\n\n==Geography==\nThe latitude 23.24 and longitude 77.4 are the geocoordinate of the Baghuwar. The local language is Hindi which is used for communication.The Pincode of the village is 487221 & the telephone code is 07793. <ref>{{cite web |title=Geography |url=https://www.indiapost.gov.in/VAS/Pages/LocatePostOffices.aspx?Pin=hIMLHC4Jl9M= |website=indiapost.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding Villages==\n* Mohad\n* Amheta\n* Khiriya\n* Biner\n* Karoda\n* Bamhori\n* Amgaon\n* Barodiya\n* Tinsara\n* Simariya Khurd\n* Pipariya\n==References==\n", "name_user": "Rajeev Gaur123", "label": "safe", "comment": "updation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baghuwar,_Madhya_Pradesh"}
{"title_page": "Lesendro", "text_new": "[[File:Belgrad-BarLineCrossingSkutariLake.jpg|thumb|Lesendro fortress, view from Belgrade - Bar railway]][[File:Lesendro causeway.jpg|thumb|Train passes Lesendro causeway]]\n'''Lesendro''' is an island and a fortress in [[Skadar Lake]] in [[Montenegro]]. It is located near the small town of [[Vranjina]]. The fort was built in the 18th century. It is located on a peninsula, which until the construction of the [[Belgrade - Bar railway]] was an island. \n==History==\nDuring the reign of [[Petar II Petrovi\u0107-Njego\u0161]] a fortress served as a defense against [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] attacks and provided for undisturbed fishing and trade, Petar II himself often came here to rest.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia|last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors=|title=Mala enciklopedija Prosveta|year=1985|edition=3|url= |publisher=Prosveta |location=Beograd|isbn=978-86-07-00001-2}}</ref>\n\nLesendro was 11 years under the rule of the [[Prince-Bishopric of Montenegro]], until 1843 when [[Osman Pasha (naval officer)|Osman Pasha]] occupied Lesendro, at the same time as Vranjina and the Ottoman Turks made their fortifications there. The island was liberated in 1878 along with the fortress town of [[\u017dabljak Crnojevi\u0107a]], which were annexed to the [[Principality of Montenegro]].<ref>{{Cite book |ref= harv|last=Markovi\u0107|first=Jovan |title=Enciklopedijski istorijski leksikon Jugoslavije|year=1990|url= |publisher=Svjetlost|location=Sarajevo|isbn=978-86-01-02651-3}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|42.2716|19.1197|format=dms|type:isle_region:ME|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Islands of Lake Skadar]]\n[[Category:Cetinje Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Belgrad-BarLineCrossingSkutariLake.jpg|thumb|Lesendro fortress, view from Belgrade - Bar railway]][[File:Lesendro causeway.jpg|thumb|Train passes Lesendro causeway]]\n'''Lesendro''' is an island and a fortress in [[Skadar Lake]] in [[Montenegro]]. It is located near the small town of [[Vranjina]]. The fort was built in the 18th century. It is located on a peninsula, which until the construction of the [[Belgrade - Bar railway]] was an island. \n==History==\nDuring the reign of [[Petar II Petrovi\u0107-Njego\u0161]] a fortress served as a defense against [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] attacks and provided for undisturbed fishing and trade, Petar II himself often came here to rest.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia|last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors=|title=Mala enciklopedija Prosveta|year=1985|edition=3|url= |publisher=Prosveta |location=Beograd|isbn=978-86-07-00001-2}}</ref>\n\nLesendro was 11 years under the rule of the [[Prince-Bishopric of Montenegro]], until 1843 when [[Osman Pasha]] occupied Lesendro, at the same time as Vranjina and the Ottoman Turks made their fortifications there. The island was liberated in 1878 along with the fortress town of [[\u017dabljak Crnojevi\u0107a]], which were annexed to the [[Principality of Montenegro]].<ref>{{Cite book |ref= harv|last=Markovi\u0107|first=Jovan |title=Enciklopedijski istorijski leksikon Jugoslavije|year=1990|url= |publisher=Svjetlost|location=Sarajevo|isbn=978-86-01-02651-3}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|42.2716|19.1197|format=dms|type:isle_region:ME|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Islands of Lake Skadar]]\n[[Category:Cetinje Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toOsman Pasha(link changed toOsman Pasha (naval officer)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lesendro"}
{"title_page": "Dua Lipa discography", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = [[Dua Lipa]]\n| Image        = Dua Lipa By Daniel \u00c5hs Karlsson.jpg\n| Caption      = Lipa on the Swedish television show ''[[Sommarkrysset]]'' in August 2016\n| Alt          = Refer to caption\n| Studio       = 2\n| EP           = 4\n| Singles      = 20<!-- Last counted at \"Break My Heart\" -->\n| Music videos = 21<!-- Last counted at \"Break My Heart\" -->\n| Option       = 1\n| Option name  = Reissues\n| 1Option      = 6<!-- Last counted until \"Future Nostalgia\" -->\n| 1Option name = Promotional singles\n}}\n\nEnglish singer [[Dua Lipa]] has released two [[studio album]]s, four [[extended play]]s (EPs), 16 [[Single (music)|single]]s (including four as a featured artist), 21 [[music video]]s, one [[reissue]] and six [[promotional single]]s. In 2015, Lipa released \"[[New Love (Dua Lipa song)|New Love]]\" as her debut single. Her second single \"[[Be the One (Dua Lipa song)|Be the One]]\" reached the top 10 in multiple countries and attained a double platinum [[Music certification|certification]] in Australia, Italy, Netherlands, and Poland. Her fourth and fifth singles \"[[Hotter than Hell (Dua Lipa song)|Hotter than Hell]]\" (2016) and \"[[Blow Your Mind (Mwah)]]\" (2016) both went top 30 in the UK and received platinum and gold certifications respectively. The latter also became the singer's first entry on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], peaking at number 72, and went gold. In March 2017, Lipa scored three simultaneous top 15 singles in the United Kingdom with \"[[No Lie (Sean Paul song)|No Lie]]\" (a collaboration with [[Sean Paul]]), \"Be the One\" and \"[[Scared to Be Lonely]]\" (with [[Martin Garrix]]).\n\nThat year, the singer was also featured on \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)#Artists for Grenfell Tower charity single|Bridge over Troubled Water]]\" as part of [[Artists for Grenfell]], while releasing her [[Dua Lipa (album)|eponymous debut studio album]] in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sonis |first=Rachel |url=http://www.idolator.com/7643997/dua-lipa-debut-album-cover-art |title=Dua Lipa Reveals Cover Art For Self-Titled Album |publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] |date=24 August 2016 |accessdate=24 August 2016}}</ref> The record spawned \"[[New Rules (song)|New Rules]]\" (2017), which achieved commercial success worldwide and reached number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/dua-lipas-new-rules-becomes-the-first-solo-female-uk-number-1-single-since-adele-s-hello-this-means-a-lot-__19978/|last=Copsey|first=Rob|title=Dua Lipa's New Rules becomes the first solo female UK Number 1 single since Adele's Hello: \"This means a lot\"|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=22 August 2017}}</ref> The chart-topping singles \"[[IDGAF (Dua Lipa song)|IDGAF]]\" and \"[[One Kiss (song)|One Kiss]]\" with Scottish producer [[Calvin Harris]] followed in 2018. The latter became the singer's second top 40 hit in the US, reaching number 26 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. It was later certified platinum in the country. Other singles from Lipa's debut album included \"[[Last Dance (Dua Lipa song)|Last Dance]]\", \"[[Lost in Your Light]]\" featuring American singer [[Miguel (singer)|Miguel]]\", and \"[[Homesick (Dua Lipa song)|Homesick]]\" which features uncredited vocals from [[Chris Martin]]. In 2018, the singer released \"[[Electricity (Silk City and Dua Lipa song)|Electricity]]\" in collaboration with British-American duo [[Silk City (band)|Silk City]]. It reached a peak position of number four in the UK, and peaked at number 62 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100. Along with all of Lipa's other single releases, the song appeared on a reissue of her debut album titled ''Dua Lipa: Complete Edition'', which was released on 19 October 2018.\n\nIn March 2020, Lipa released her second studio album, ''[[Future Nostalgia (Dua Lipa album)|Future Nostalgia]]''. It was preceded by the UK top-five singles \"[[Don't Start Now (Dua Lipa song)|Don't Start Now]]\" and \"[[Physical (Dua Lipa song)|Physical]]\". \"Don't Start Now\" also became Lipa's highest-charting single in the US where it reached number two on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.\n\n==Albums==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+List of studio albums, with selected chart positions, sales and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:9em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Certifications\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br><ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48638/dua-lipa/ |title=Dua Lipa |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=\"AUS\">Peak chart positions in Australia:\n* All except noted: {{cite web |url=https://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Dua+Lipa |title=Discography Dua Lipa |publisher=australian-charts.com |accessdate=3 May 2016}}\n* \"Blow Your Mind (Mwah)\": {{cite web|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/australian-singles-the-chainsmokers-and-halsey-spend-seven-weeks-at-no-1-20160926|title=Australian Singles: The Chainsmokers and Halsey Spend Seven Weeks At No 1|publisher=Noise11|last=Ryan|first=Gavin|date=26 September 2016|accessdate=26 September 2016}}\n* \"Want To\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2018/9/aria-chart-watch-492/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #492|publisher=auspOp|date=29 September 2018|accessdate=29 September 2018}}\n* \"Swan Song\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2019/2/aria-chart-watch-510/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #510|publisher=auspOp|date=2 February 2019|accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL (FL)]]<br><ref name=\"BEL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Dua+Lipa |title=Discografie Dua Lipa |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Ultratop]] |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br/><ref name=\"CAN-albums\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/dua-lipa/chart-history/CNA|title=Dua Lipa Chart History: Canadian Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br><ref name=\"GER\">{{cite web |url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/suche?artistId=Dua+Lipa |title=Discographie von Dua Lipa |language=German |publisher=Offizielle Deutsche Charts |accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br><ref name=\"IRE\">{{cite web |url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Dua+Lipa |title=Discography Dua Lipa |publisher=irish-charts.com |accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[MegaCharts|NL]]<br><ref name=\"NL\">{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Dua+Lipa|title=Discografie Dua Lipa|publisher=dutchcharts.nl|language=Dutch|accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br><ref name=\"NZ\">{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Dua+Lipa|title=Discography Dua Lipa|publisher=charts.nz|accessdate=6 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Sverigetopplistan|SWE]]<br><ref name=\"SWE\">{{cite web|url=https://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Dua+Lipa|title=Discography 