{"title_page": "Gideon Davies", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Gideon Davies\n| birth_name       = Gideon John Davies\n| image             = Professor_Gideon_Davies,_FRS,_FMedSci.jpg\n| caption           = Gideon Davies in 2010\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1964|7|6|df=y}}<ref name=whoswho>{{Who's Who | surname = DAVIES | othernames = Prof. Gideon John | id = U251693 | volume = 2014 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n| nationality       = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| birth_place       = [[Great Sutton]], [[Cheshire]]\n| fields            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Structural biology|Structural]] [[Enzymology]]\n* [[Carbohydrate]] [[Biochemistry]]\n* [[Glycobiology]]\n* [[Biofuel]]s<ref name=googlescholar/>}}\n| workplaces        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University of York]]\n* [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|CNRS]] [[Grenoble]]\n* [[European Molecular Biology Laboratory|EMBL]] [[Hamburg]]\n* [[University of British Columbia]]<ref name=volcado>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 11518970\n| year = 2001\n| last1 = Vocadlo\n| first1 = D. J.\n| title = Catalysis by hen egg-white lysozyme proceeds via a covalent intermediate\n| journal = Nature\n| volume = 412\n| issue = 6849\n| pages = 835\u20138\n| last2 = Davies\n| first2 = G. J.\n| last3 = Laine\n| first3 = R\n| last4 = Withers\n| first4 = S. G.\n| doi = 10.1038/35090602\n| url = http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/131/1/daviesgj1.pdf\n}}</ref>}}\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Bristol]] (BSc, PhD, DSc)\n| thesis_title      = Phosphoglycerate kinase from Bacillus stearothermophilus\n| thesis_url        = http://pmt-eu.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?doc=44BU_LMS_DS000508244&vid=44BU_VU1\n| thesis_year       = 1990\n| doctoral_advisor  = {{Plainlist|\n* Herman Watson\n* Len Hall<ref name=bio>[http://www.york.ac.uk/res/daviesgroup/biography.htm Professor Gideon Davies, FMedSci, FRS Biography], University of York</ref>}}\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  =\n| known_for         =\n| awards            = {{Plainlist|\n* [https://www.queensanniversaryprizes.org.uk/winners/ground-breaking-research-in-protein-science-leading-to-new-drugs-and-therapies-for-diabetes-and-other-conditions-and-improved-industrial-processes/ Queen's Anniversary Prize (to YSBL)] (2019)\n* [https://www.rsc.org/Membership/Networking/InterestGroups/Carbohydrate/Haworth/ Haworth Memorial Lectureship of Royal Society of Chemistry] (2018)\n* [https://www.icheme.org/career/events/awards/global-awards/past-winners/ Global Energy Award of Institution of Chemical Engineers] (2016)\n* [[Davy Medal]] (2015)\n* [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|FMedSci]] (2014)\n* [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (2010)<ref name=royal/>\n* [[European Molecular Biology Organization|EMBO]] member (2010)\n* [[Gabor Medal]] (2010)\n* [[Doctor of Science|DSc]] (2007)<ref name=dsc/>\n* [[Royal Society of Chemistry|FRSC]] (2002)}}\n| website           = {{Plainlist|\n* {{URL|http://www.york.ac.uk/chemistry/staff/academic/d-g/gdavies}}}}\n| spouse            = Val\u00e9rie Marie-Andr\u00e9e Ducros<ref name=whoswho/>\n| children          = Two daughters<ref name=whoswho/>\n}}'''Gideon John Davies''' (born 1964) [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Chemistry|FRSC]] [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|FMedSci]] is a [https://royalsociety.org/news/2016/09/leading-scientists-awarded-royal-society-research-professorships/ Royal Society Ken Murray Research Professor] in the York [[Structural biology|Structural Biology]] Laboratory (YSBL) at the [[University of York]], in the UK.<ref name=googlescholar>{{GoogleScholar|6rHWVvgAAAAJ}}</ref><ref name=microsoft>{{AcademicSearch|18607041}}</ref><ref name=scopus>{{Scopus|id=35517179900}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nDavies was educated at the [[University of Bristol]] where he was awarded a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Biochemistry]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in 1990 for research on the enzyme [[phosphoglycerate kinase]] isolated from the bacterium ''[[Bacillus stearothermophilus]]'', and supervised by Herman Watson and Len Hall.<ref name=bio/><ref name=phd>{{cite thesis |degree=PhD |first=Gideon John|last=Davies |title=Phosphoglycerate kinase from Bacillus stearothermophilus  |publisher=University of Bristol |date=1990 |url=http://pmt-eu.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?doc=44BU_LMS_DS000508244&vid=44BU_VU1}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing his PhD, Davies did [[postdoctoral research]] at the [[European Molecular Biology Laboratory|European Molecular Biology Laboratory (EMBL)]] outstation in Hamburg working with Keith S. Wilson on the use of [[synchrotron radiation]] in [[protein]] [[crystallography]] and also at the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|Centre national de la recherche scientifique (CNRS)]] in [[Grenoble]].<ref name=york/> in 1990, Davies moved to York to work with Dale Wigley and [[Guy Dodson]] on [[DNA gyrase]], starting his own group within YSBL in 1996 upon receiving a [[Royal Society]] University Research Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/gideon-davies-6769/|title=Gideon Davies|website=royalsociety.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-06-14}}</ref>. He was appointed Professor at the University of York in 2001<ref name=york/> and awarded a Royal Society Ken Murray Research Professorship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/news/2016/09/leading-scientists-awarded-royal-society-research-professorships/|title=Leading scientists awarded Royal Society Research Professorships|website=royalsociety.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-06-14}}</ref> in 2016. He has collaborated with [[Alwyn Jones (biophysicist)|Alywn Jones]], Bernard Henrissat,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0959-440X(97)80072-3| title = Structural and sequence-based classification of glycoside hydrolases| journal = Current Opinion in Structural Biology| volume = 7| issue = 5| pages = 637\u201344| year = 1997| last1 = Henrissat | first1 = B. | last2 = Davies | first2 = G. | pmid=9345621}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0969-2126(01)00220-9| title = Structures and mechanisms of glycosyl hydrolases| journal = Structure| volume = 3| issue = 9| pages = 853\u20139| year = 1995| last1 = Davies | first1 = G. | last2 = Henrissat | first2 = B. | pmid=8535779}}</ref> Steve Withers and David Vocadlo.<ref name=volcado/>\n\n==Research==\nDavies research investigates the [[biochemistry|biological chemistry]] of [[carbohydrate]]s, from their structure<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Agirre|first=Jon|last2=Davies|first2=Gideon|last3=Wilson|first3=Keith|last4=Cowtan|first4=Kevin|title=Carbohydrate anomalies in the PDB|journal=Nature Chemical Biology|volume=11|issue=5|pages=303|doi=10.1038/nchembio.1798|pmid=25885951|year=2015|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/95242/1/AgirreDaviesWIlsonCowtan_self_archived.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Agirre|first=Jon|last2=Iglesias-Fern\u00e1ndez|first2=Javier|last3=Rovira|first3=Carme|last4=Davies|first4=Gideon J|last5=Wilson|first5=Keith S|last6=Cowtan|first6=Kevin D|title=Privateer: software for the conformational validation of carbohydrate structures|journal=Nature Structural & Molecular Biology|volume=22|issue=11|pages=833\u2013834|doi=10.1038/nsmb.3115|pmid=26581513|year=2015|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/95794/1/Privateer_selfarchived.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Agirre|first=Jon|last2=Davies|first2=Gideon J|last3=Wilson|first3=Keith S|last4=Cowtan|first4=Kevin D|date=June 2017|title=Carbohydrate structure: the rocky road to automation|journal=Current Opinion in Structural Biology|series=Carbohydrates: A feast of structural glycobiology \u2022 Sequences and topology: Computational studies of protein-protein interactions|volume=44|pages=39\u201347|doi=10.1016/j.sbi.2016.11.011|pmid=27940408|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/109296/1/COStBi_postprint.pdf}}</ref> to their roles in [[enzymology]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vocadlo|first=D. J.|last2=Davies|first2=G. J.|last3=Laine|first3=R.|last4=Withers|first4=S. G.|date=2001-08-23|title=Catalysis by hen egg-white lysozyme proceeds via a covalent intermediate|journal=Nature|volume=412|issue=6849|pages=835\u2013838|doi=10.1038/35090602|issn=0028-0836|pmid=11518970|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/131/1/daviesgj1.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ducros|first=Val\u00e9rie M.-A.|last2=Zechel|first2=David L.|last3=Murshudov|first3=Garib N.|last4=Gilbert|first4=Harry J.|authorlink4=Harry J. Gilbert|last5=Szab\u00f3|first5=L\u00f3r\u00e1nd|last6=Stoll|first6=Dominik|last7=Withers|first7=Stephen G.|last8=Davies|first8=Gideon J.|date=2002-08-02|title=Substrate distortion by a beta-mannanase: snapshots of the Michaelis and covalent-intermediate complexes suggest a B(2,5) conformation for the transition state|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition in English|volume=41|issue=15|pages=2824\u20132827|doi=10.1002/1521-3773(20020802)41:15<2824::AID-ANIE2824>3.0.CO;2-G|issn=1433-7851|pmid=12203498}}</ref>, [[glycobiology]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coutinho|first=Pedro M.|last2=Deleury|first2=Emeline|last3=Davies|first3=Gideon J.|last4=Henrissat|first4=Bernard|date=2003-04-25|title=An evolving hierarchical family classification for glycosyltransferases|journal=Journal of Molecular Biology|volume=328|issue=2|pages=307\u2013317|issn=0022-2836|pmid=12691742|doi=10.1016/s0022-2836(03)00307-3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yuzwa|first=Scott A|last2=Macauley|first2=Matthew S|last3=Heinonen|first3=Julia E|last4=Shan|first4=Xiaoyang|last5=Dennis|first5=Rebecca J|last6=He|first6=Yuan|last7=Whitworth|first7=Garrett E|last8=Stubbs|first8=Keith A|last9=McEachern|first9=Ernest J|title=A potent mechanism-inspired O-GlcNAcase inhibitor that blocks phosphorylation of tau in vivo|journal=Nature Chemical Biology|volume=4|issue=8|pages=483\u2013490|doi=10.1038/nchembio.96|pmid=18587388|year=2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Liang|last2=Viola|first2=Cristina M|last3=Brzozowski|first3=Andrzej M|last4=Davies|first4=Gideon J|title=Structural characterization of human heparanase reveals insights into substrate recognition|journal=Nature Structural & Molecular Biology|volume=22|issue=12|pages=1016\u20131022|doi=10.1038/nsmb.3136|pmid=26575439|pmc=5008439|year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roth|first=Christian|last2=Chan|first2=Sherry|last3=Offen|first3=Wendy A|last4=Hemsworth|first4=Glyn R|last5=Willems|first5=Lianne I|last6=King|first6=Dustin T|last7=Varghese|first7=Vimal|last8=Britton|first8=Robert|last9=Vocadlo|first9=David J|title=Structural and functional insight into human O-GlcNAcase|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/117506/|journal=Nature Chemical Biology|volume=13|issue=6|pages=610\u2013612|doi=10.1038/nchembio.2358|pmid=28346405|pmc=5438047|year=2017}}</ref>, use as [[biofuel]]s<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yin|first=DeLu (Tyler)|last2=Urresti|first2=Saioa|last3=Lafond|first3=Mickael|last4=Johnston|first4=Esther M.|last5=Derikvand|first5=Fatemeh|last6=Ciano|first6=Luisa|last7=Berrin|first7=Jean-Guy|last8=Henrissat|first8=Bernard|last9=Walton|first9=Paul H.|date=2015-12-18|title=Structure-function characterization reveals new catalytic diversity in the galactose oxidase and glyoxal oxidase family|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=6|pages=10197|doi=10.1038/ncomms10197|pmc=4703870|pmid=26680532}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Quinlan|first=R. Jason|last2=Sweeney|first2=Matt D.|last3=Leggio|first3=Leila Lo|last4=Otten|first4=Harm|last5=Poulsen|first5=Jens-Christian N.|last6=Johansen|first6=Katja Salomon|last7=Krogh|first7=Kristian B. R. M.|last8=J\u00f8rgensen|first8=Christian Isak|last9=Tovborg|first9=Morten|date=2011-09-13|title=Insights into the oxidative degradation of cellulose by a copper metalloenzyme that exploits biomass components|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=108|issue=37|pages=15079\u201315084|doi=10.1073/pnas.1105776108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3174640|pmid=21876164}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frandsen|first=Kristian E H|last2=Simmons|first2=Thomas J|last3=Dupree|first3=Paul|last4=Poulsen|first4=Jens-Christian N|last5=Hemsworth|first5=Glyn R|last6=Ciano|first6=Luisa|last7=Johnston|first7=Esther M|last8=Tovborg|first8=Morten|last9=Johansen|first9=Katja S|title=The molecular basis of polysaccharide cleavage by lytic polysaccharide monooxygenases|journal=Nature Chemical Biology|doi=10.1038/nchembio.2029|volume=12|issue=4|pages=298\u2013303|pmid=26928935|pmc=4817220|year=2016}}</ref> and implications for gut microbiota<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Larsbrink|first=Johan|last2=Rogers|first2=Theresa E.|last3=Hemsworth|first3=Glyn R.|last4=McKee|first4=Lauren S.|last5=Tauzin|first5=Alexandra S.|last6=Spadiut|first6=Oliver|last7=Klinter|first7=Stefan|last8=Pudlo|first8=Nicholas A.|last9=Urs|first9=Karthik|title=A discrete genetic locus confers xyloglucan metabolism in select human gut Bacteroidetes|journal=Nature|volume=506|issue=7489|pages=498\u2013502|doi=10.1038/nature12907|pmc=4282169|pmid=24463512|year=2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cuskin|first=Fiona|last2=Lowe|first2=Elisabeth C.|last3=Temple|first3=Max J.|last4=Zhu|first4=Yanping|last5=Cameron|first5=Elizabeth A.|last6=Pudlo|first6=Nicholas A.|last7=Porter|first7=Nathan T.|last8=Urs|first8=Karthik|last9=Thompson|first9=Andrew J.|title=Human gut Bacteroidetes can utilize yeast mannan through a selfish mechanism|journal=Nature|volume=517|issue=7533|pages=165\u2013169|doi=10.1038/nature13995|pmid=25567280|year=2015|pmc=4978465}}</ref>. His research  has been funded by the [[Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council|Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC)]]<ref name=rcuk>[http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk/person/2EC0C60C-8CD1-4B1B-8B7F-DDFD8B81671A UK Government research grants awarded to Gideon Davies], via [[Research Councils UK]]</ref>, [[European Research Council|European Research Council (ERC)]] and [[Alzheimer's Research UK]]<ref name=\"york\">[http://www.york.ac.uk/chemistry/staff/academic/d-g/gdavies Professor Gideon Davies, FMedSci, FRS], University of York</ref>.\n\n==Awards and honours==\nDavies was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society|Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS)]] in 2010. His nomination reads: {{centered pull quote|Professor Gideon Davies' research is focused on \"structural enzymology\". In this he addresses the enzymes, and their [[protein domain|accessory domains]], that are involved in the synthesis, modification and breakdown of carbohydrates. His chemical and structural insight into [[Protein\u2013carbohydrate interactions|protein-carbohydrate interactions]] and his brilliant exploitation of advanced crystallographic methods provide the basis for understanding how the chemical and structural factors in the [[stereochemistry|stereochemical]] pathway of the [[Enzyme substrate (biology)|enzyme:substrate complex]] govern specificity and catalysis. His research is having an immense impact on carbohydrate chemistry and biology and biological catalysis generally.<ref name=royal>{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/fellowship/2010/gideon-davies/ |title=Professor Gideon John Davies FRS |publisher=The Royal Society |archivedate=2014-10-25 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TaQHUrgj?url=https://royalsociety.org/people/fellowship/2010/gideon-davies/ |location=London |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nDavies was elected a [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|Fellow of the Academy of Medical Sciences (FMedSci)]] in 2014, his nomination reads{{centered pull quote|Gideon Davies, who is Professor of Biological Chemistry at University of York, has made world-leading contributions to Biochemistry. He has made fundamental additions to our understanding of enzyme mechanism and carbohydrate biochemistry. As a direct result of his work into the conformation of sugars during turnover, he described the [[rational design]] of [[Enzyme inhibitor|highly potent inhibitors]] of [[O-linked glycosylation|O-linked glucosamine modifying enzymes]]. These compounds are showing potential as treatments for [[Alzheimer's disease]]. Recently he has turned to study the human [[Microbiome|microbiota]], which are now recognised to be an essential component of human health, and their carbohydrate [[metabolism]] is implicated in several disease states.<ref name=fmedsci>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-gideon-davies/ |title=Professor Gideon Davies FRS FMedSci |publisher=The Academy of Medical Sciences |archivedate=2014-10-25 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TaQ10yUR?url=http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-gideon-davies/ |location=London |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nDavies was elected a member of the [[European Molecular Biology Organization|European Molecular Biology Organization (EMBO)]] in 2010,<ref name=york/> is a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] (FRSC) and was awarded a [[Doctor of Science|Doctor of Science (DSc)]] degree from the [[University of Bristol]] in 2007.<ref name=dsc>{{cite thesis |degree=DSc |first=Gideon John|last=Davies |title=Published work submitted for the degree of D.Sc.  |publisher=University of Bristol |date=2007 |url=http://pmt-eu.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?doc=44BU_LMS_DS000753185&vid=44BU_VU1}}</ref>\n\nDavies has won a number of awards for his work.  These include The Davy and Gabor Medals of the [[Royal Society]], the Haworth Memorial, Khorana, Peptide and Protein, Corday-Morgan and Carbohydrate Chemistry medals of the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]], the iChemE Global Energy Award (with [https://www.york.ac.uk/chemistry/staff/academic/t-z/pwalton/ Paul Walton] and [http://www.afmb.univ-mrs.fr/Bernard-Henrissat?lang=en Bernard Henrissat]) of the [[Institution of Chemical Engineers]], The Whistler Prize of the [https://ico.chemistry.unimelb.edu.au/ International Carbohydrate Organization], and the [https://www.biochemistry.org/grants-and-awards/awards/glaxosmithcline-award/ GlaxoSmithKline Award] of the [[Biochemical Society]]. In 2019 he was one of the members of the York Structural Biology Laboratory at the [[University of York]] that received the [[Queen's Anniversary Prize]]. \n\n==Personal life==\nDavies married Val\u00e9rie Marie-Andr\u00e9e Ducros<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nsb0498-310| pmid = 9546223| title = Crystal structure of the type-2 Cu depleted laccase from Coprinus dnereus at 2.2 \u00c5 resolution| journal = Nature Structural Biology| volume = 5| issue = 4| pages = 310\u2013316| year = 1998| last1 = Ducros | first1 = V. R. | last2 = Brzozowski | first2 = A. M. | last3 = Wilson | first3 = K. S. | last4 = Brown | first4 = S. H. | last5 = \u00d8stergaard | first5 = P. | last6 = Schneider | first6 = P. | last7 = Yaver | first7 = D. S. | last8 = Pedersen | first8 = A. H. | last9 = Davies | first9 = G. J. \n}}</ref> in 1999 and has two daughters.<ref name=whoswho/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}{{FRS 2010}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Gideon John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of York]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Molecular Biology Organization]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Gideon Davies\n| birth_name       = Gideon John Davies\n| image             = Professor_Gideon_Davies,_FRS,_FMedSci.jpg\n| caption           = Gideon Davies in 2010\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1964|7|6|df=y}}<ref name=whoswho>{{Who's Who | surname = DAVIES | othernames = Prof. Gideon John | id = U251693 | volume = 2014 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n| nationality       = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| birth_place       = [[Great Sutton]], [[Cheshire]]\n| fields            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Structural biology|Structural]] [[Enzymology]]\n* [[Carbohydrate]] [[Biochemistry]]\n* [[Glycobiology]]\n* [[Biofuel]]s<ref name=googlescholar/>}}\n| workplaces        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University of York]]\n* [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|CNRS]] [[Grenoble]]\n* [[European Molecular Biology Laboratory|EMBL]] [[Hamburg]]\n* [[University of British Columbia]]<ref name=volcado>{{Cite journal\n | pmid = 11518970\n| year = 2001\n| last1 = Vocadlo\n| first1 = D. J.\n| title = Catalysis by hen egg-white lysozyme proceeds via a covalent intermediate\n| journal = Nature\n| volume = 412\n| issue = 6849\n| pages = 835\u20138\n| last2 = Davies\n| first2 = G. J.\n| last3 = Laine\n| first3 = R\n| last4 = Withers\n| first4 = S. G.\n| doi = 10.1038/35090602\n| url = http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/131/1/daviesgj1.pdf\n}}</ref>}}\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Bristol]] (BSc, PhD, DSc)\n| thesis_title      = Phosphoglycerate kinase from Bacillus stearothermophilus\n| thesis_url        = http://pmt-eu.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?doc=44BU_LMS_DS000508244&vid=44BU_VU1\n| thesis_year       = 1990\n| doctoral_advisor  = {{Plainlist|\n* Herman Watson\n* Len Hall<ref name=bio>[http://www.york.ac.uk/res/daviesgroup/biography.htm Professor Gideon Davies, FMedSci, FRS Biography], University of York</ref>}}\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  =\n| known_for         =\n| awards            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Davy Medal]] (2015)\n* [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|FMedSci]] (2014)\n* [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (2010)<ref name=royal/>\n* [[European Molecular Biology Organization|EMBO]] member (2010)\n* [[Gabor Medal]] (2010)\n* [[Doctor of Science|DSc]] (2007)<ref name=dsc/>\n* [[Royal Society of Chemistry|FRSC]] (2002)}}\n| website           = {{Plainlist|\n* {{URL|http://www.york.ac.uk/res/daviesgroup}}\n* {{URL|http://www.york.ac.uk/chemistry/staff/academic/d-g/gdavies}}}}\n| spouse            = Val\u00e9rie Marie-Andr\u00e9e Ducros<ref name=whoswho/>\n| children          = Two daughters<ref name=whoswho/>\n}}'''Gideon John Davies''' (born 1964) [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Chemistry|FRSC]] [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|FMedSci]] is a [https://royalsociety.org/news/2016/09/leading-scientists-awarded-royal-society-research-professorships/ Royal Society Ken Murray Research Professor] in the York [[Structural biology|Structural Biology]] Laboratory (YSBL) at the [[University of York]], in the UK.<ref name=googlescholar>{{GoogleScholar|6rHWVvgAAAAJ}}</ref><ref name=microsoft>{{AcademicSearch|18607041}}</ref><ref name=scopus>{{Scopus|id=35517179900}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nDavies was educated at the [[University of Bristol]] where he was awarded a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Biochemistry]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in 1990 for research on the enzyme [[phosphoglycerate kinase]] isolated from the bacterium ''[[Bacillus stearothermophilus]]'', and supervised by Herman Watson and Len Hall.<ref name=bio/><ref name=phd>{{cite thesis |degree=PhD |first=Gideon John|last=Davies |title=Phosphoglycerate kinase from Bacillus stearothermophilus  |publisher=University of Bristol |date=1990 |url=http://pmt-eu.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?doc=44BU_LMS_DS000508244&vid=44BU_VU1}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing his PhD, Davies did [[postdoctoral research]] at the [[European Molecular Biology Laboratory|European Molecular Biology Laboratory (EMBL)]] outstation in Hamburg working with Keith S. Wilson on the use of [[synchrotron radiation]] in [[protein]] [[crystallography]] and also at the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|Centre national de la recherche scientifique (CNRS)]] in [[Grenoble]].<ref name=york/> in 1990, Davies moved to York to work with Dale Wigley and [[Guy Dodson]] on [[DNA gyrase]], starting his own group within YSBL in 1996 upon receiving a [[Royal Society]] University Research Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/gideon-davies-6769/|title=Gideon Davies|website=royalsociety.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-06-14}}</ref>. He was appointed Professor at the University of York in 2001<ref name=york/> and awarded a Royal Society Ken Murray Research Professorship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/news/2016/09/leading-scientists-awarded-royal-society-research-professorships/|title=Leading scientists awarded Royal Society Research Professorships|website=royalsociety.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-06-14}}</ref> in 2016. He has collaborated with [[Alwyn Jones (biophysicist)|Alywn Jones]], Bernard Henrissat,<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0959-440X(97)80072-3| title = Structural and sequence-based classification of glycoside hydrolases| journal = Current Opinion in Structural Biology| volume = 7| issue = 5| pages = 637\u201344| year = 1997| last1 = Henrissat | first1 = B. | last2 = Davies | first2 = G. | pmid=9345621}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0969-2126(01)00220-9| title = Structures and mechanisms of glycosyl hydrolases| journal = Structure| volume = 3| issue = 9| pages = 853\u20139| year = 1995| last1 = Davies | first1 = G. | last2 = Henrissat | first2 = B. | pmid=8535779}}</ref> Steve Withers and David Vocadlo.<ref name=volcado/>\n\n==Research==\nDavies research investigates the [[biochemistry|biological chemistry]] of [[carbohydrate]]s, from their structure<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Agirre|first=Jon|last2=Davies|first2=Gideon|last3=Wilson|first3=Keith|last4=Cowtan|first4=Kevin|title=Carbohydrate anomalies in the PDB|journal=Nature Chemical Biology|volume=11|issue=5|pages=303|doi=10.1038/nchembio.1798|pmid=25885951|year=2015|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/95242/1/AgirreDaviesWIlsonCowtan_self_archived.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Agirre|first=Jon|last2=Iglesias-Fern\u00e1ndez|first2=Javier|last3=Rovira|first3=Carme|last4=Davies|first4=Gideon J|last5=Wilson|first5=Keith S|last6=Cowtan|first6=Kevin D|title=Privateer: software for the conformational validation of carbohydrate structures|journal=Nature Structural & Molecular Biology|volume=22|issue=11|pages=833\u2013834|doi=10.1038/nsmb.3115|pmid=26581513|year=2015|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/95794/1/Privateer_selfarchived.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Agirre|first=Jon|last2=Davies|first2=Gideon J|last3=Wilson|first3=Keith S|last4=Cowtan|first4=Kevin D|date=June 2017|title=Carbohydrate structure: the rocky road to automation|journal=Current Opinion in Structural Biology|series=Carbohydrates: A feast of structural glycobiology \u2022 Sequences and topology: Computational studies of protein-protein interactions|volume=44|pages=39\u201347|doi=10.1016/j.sbi.2016.11.011|pmid=27940408|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/109296/1/COStBi_postprint.pdf}}</ref> to their roles in [[enzymology]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vocadlo|first=D. J.|last2=Davies|first2=G. J.|last3=Laine|first3=R.|last4=Withers|first4=S. G.|date=2001-08-23|title=Catalysis by hen egg-white lysozyme proceeds via a covalent intermediate|journal=Nature|volume=412|issue=6849|pages=835\u2013838|doi=10.1038/35090602|issn=0028-0836|pmid=11518970|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/131/1/daviesgj1.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ducros|first=Val\u00e9rie M.-A.|last2=Zechel|first2=David L.|last3=Murshudov|first3=Garib N.|last4=Gilbert|first4=Harry J.|authorlink4=Harry J. Gilbert|last5=Szab\u00f3|first5=L\u00f3r\u00e1nd|last6=Stoll|first6=Dominik|last7=Withers|first7=Stephen G.|last8=Davies|first8=Gideon J.|date=2002-08-02|title=Substrate distortion by a beta-mannanase: snapshots of the Michaelis and covalent-intermediate complexes suggest a B(2,5) conformation for the transition state|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition in English|volume=41|issue=15|pages=2824\u20132827|doi=10.1002/1521-3773(20020802)41:15<2824::AID-ANIE2824>3.0.CO;2-G|issn=1433-7851|pmid=12203498}}</ref>, [[glycobiology]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coutinho|first=Pedro M.|last2=Deleury|first2=Emeline|last3=Davies|first3=Gideon J.|last4=Henrissat|first4=Bernard|date=2003-04-25|title=An evolving hierarchical family classification for glycosyltransferases|journal=Journal of Molecular Biology|volume=328|issue=2|pages=307\u2013317|issn=0022-2836|pmid=12691742|doi=10.1016/s0022-2836(03)00307-3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yuzwa|first=Scott A|last2=Macauley|first2=Matthew S|last3=Heinonen|first3=Julia E|last4=Shan|first4=Xiaoyang|last5=Dennis|first5=Rebecca J|last6=He|first6=Yuan|last7=Whitworth|first7=Garrett E|last8=Stubbs|first8=Keith A|last9=McEachern|first9=Ernest J|title=A potent mechanism-inspired O-GlcNAcase inhibitor that blocks phosphorylation of tau in vivo|journal=Nature Chemical Biology|volume=4|issue=8|pages=483\u2013490|doi=10.1038/nchembio.96|pmid=18587388|year=2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Liang|last2=Viola|first2=Cristina M|last3=Brzozowski|first3=Andrzej M|last4=Davies|first4=Gideon J|title=Structural characterization of human heparanase reveals insights into substrate recognition|journal=Nature Structural & Molecular Biology|volume=22|issue=12|pages=1016\u20131022|doi=10.1038/nsmb.3136|pmid=26575439|pmc=5008439|year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roth|first=Christian|last2=Chan|first2=Sherry|last3=Offen|first3=Wendy A|last4=Hemsworth|first4=Glyn R|last5=Willems|first5=Lianne I|last6=King|first6=Dustin T|last7=Varghese|first7=Vimal|last8=Britton|first8=Robert|last9=Vocadlo|first9=David J|title=Structural and functional insight into human O-GlcNAcase|url=http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/117506/|journal=Nature Chemical Biology|volume=13|issue=6|pages=610\u2013612|doi=10.1038/nchembio.2358|pmid=28346405|pmc=5438047|year=2017}}</ref>, use as [[biofuel]]s<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yin|first=DeLu (Tyler)|last2=Urresti|first2=Saioa|last3=Lafond|first3=Mickael|last4=Johnston|first4=Esther M.|last5=Derikvand|first5=Fatemeh|last6=Ciano|first6=Luisa|last7=Berrin|first7=Jean-Guy|last8=Henrissat|first8=Bernard|last9=Walton|first9=Paul H.|date=2015-12-18|title=Structure-function characterization reveals new catalytic diversity in the galactose oxidase and glyoxal oxidase family|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=6|pages=10197|doi=10.1038/ncomms10197|pmc=4703870|pmid=26680532}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Quinlan|first=R. Jason|last2=Sweeney|first2=Matt D.|last3=Leggio|first3=Leila Lo|last4=Otten|first4=Harm|last5=Poulsen|first5=Jens-Christian N.|last6=Johansen|first6=Katja Salomon|last7=Krogh|first7=Kristian B. R. M.|last8=J\u00f8rgensen|first8=Christian Isak|last9=Tovborg|first9=Morten|date=2011-09-13|title=Insights into the oxidative degradation of cellulose by a copper metalloenzyme that exploits biomass components|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=108|issue=37|pages=15079\u201315084|doi=10.1073/pnas.1105776108|issn=0027-8424|pmc=3174640|pmid=21876164}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frandsen|first=Kristian E H|last2=Simmons|first2=Thomas J|last3=Dupree|first3=Paul|last4=Poulsen|first4=Jens-Christian N|last5=Hemsworth|first5=Glyn R|last6=Ciano|first6=Luisa|last7=Johnston|first7=Esther M|last8=Tovborg|first8=Morten|last9=Johansen|first9=Katja S|title=The molecular basis of polysaccharide cleavage by lytic polysaccharide monooxygenases|journal=Nature Chemical Biology|doi=10.1038/nchembio.2029|volume=12|issue=4|pages=298\u2013303|pmid=26928935|pmc=4817220|year=2016}}</ref> and implications for gut microbiota<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Larsbrink|first=Johan|last2=Rogers|first2=Theresa E.|last3=Hemsworth|first3=Glyn R.|last4=McKee|first4=Lauren S.|last5=Tauzin|first5=Alexandra S.|last6=Spadiut|first6=Oliver|last7=Klinter|first7=Stefan|last8=Pudlo|first8=Nicholas A.|last9=Urs|first9=Karthik|title=A discrete genetic locus confers xyloglucan metabolism in select human gut Bacteroidetes|journal=Nature|volume=506|issue=7489|pages=498\u2013502|doi=10.1038/nature12907|pmc=4282169|pmid=24463512|year=2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cuskin|first=Fiona|last2=Lowe|first2=Elisabeth C.|last3=Temple|first3=Max J.|last4=Zhu|first4=Yanping|last5=Cameron|first5=Elizabeth A.|last6=Pudlo|first6=Nicholas A.|last7=Porter|first7=Nathan T.|last8=Urs|first8=Karthik|last9=Thompson|first9=Andrew J.|title=Human gut Bacteroidetes can utilize yeast mannan through a selfish mechanism|journal=Nature|volume=517|issue=7533|pages=165\u2013169|doi=10.1038/nature13995|pmid=25567280|year=2015|pmc=4978465}}</ref>. His research  has been funded by the [[Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council|Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC)]]<ref name=rcuk>[http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk/person/2EC0C60C-8CD1-4B1B-8B7F-DDFD8B81671A UK Government research grants awarded to Gideon Davies], via [[Research Councils UK]]</ref>, [[European Research Council|European Research Council (ERC)]] and [[Alzheimer's Research UK]]<ref name=\"york\">[http://www.york.ac.uk/chemistry/staff/academic/d-g/gdavies Professor Gideon Davies, FMedSci, FRS], University of York</ref>.\n\n==Awards and honours==\nDavies was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society|Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS)]] in 2010. His nomination reads: {{centered pull quote|Professor Gideon Davies' research is focused on \"structural enzymology\". In this he addresses the enzymes, and their [[protein domain|accessory domains]], that are involved in the synthesis, modification and breakdown of carbohydrates. His chemical and structural insight into [[Protein\u2013carbohydrate interactions|protein-carbohydrate interactions]] and his brilliant exploitation of advanced crystallographic methods provide the basis for understanding how the chemical and structural factors in the [[stereochemistry|stereochemical]] pathway of the [[Enzyme substrate (biology)|enzyme:substrate complex]] govern specificity and catalysis. His research is having an immense impact on carbohydrate chemistry and biology and biological catalysis generally.<ref name=royal>{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/fellowship/2010/gideon-davies/ |title=Professor Gideon John Davies FRS |publisher=The Royal Society |archivedate=2014-10-25 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TaQHUrgj?url=https://royalsociety.org/people/fellowship/2010/gideon-davies/ |location=London |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nDavies was elected a [[Academy of Medical Sciences, United Kingdom|Fellow of the Academy of Medical Sciences (FMedSci)]] in 2014, his nomination reads{{centered pull quote|Gideon Davies, who is Professor of Biological Chemistry at University of York, has made world-leading contributions to Biochemistry. He has made fundamental additions to our understanding of enzyme mechanism and carbohydrate biochemistry. As a direct result of his work into the conformation of sugars during turnover, he described the [[rational design]] of [[Enzyme inhibitor|highly potent inhibitors]] of [[O-linked glycosylation|O-linked glucosamine modifying enzymes]]. These compounds are showing potential as treatments for [[Alzheimer's disease]]. Recently he has turned to study the human [[Microbiome|microbiota]], which are now recognised to be an essential component of human health, and their carbohydrate [[metabolism]] is implicated in several disease states.<ref name=fmedsci>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-gideon-davies/ |title=Professor Gideon Davies FRS FMedSci |publisher=The Academy of Medical Sciences |archivedate=2014-10-25 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TaQ10yUR?url=http://www.acmedsci.ac.uk/fellows/fellows-directory/ordinary-fellows/professor-gideon-davies/ |location=London |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n\nDavies was elected a member of the [[European Molecular Biology Organization|European Molecular Biology Organization (EMBO)]] in 2010,<ref name=york/> is a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] (FRSC) and was awarded a [[Doctor of Science|Doctor of Science (DSc)]] degree from the [[University of Bristol]] in 2007.<ref name=dsc>{{cite thesis |degree=DSc |first=Gideon John|last=Davies |title=Published work submitted for the degree of D.Sc.  |publisher=University of Bristol |date=2007 |url=http://pmt-eu.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/display.do?doc=44BU_LMS_DS000753185&vid=44BU_VU1}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDavies married Val\u00e9rie Marie-Andr\u00e9e Ducros<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nsb0498-310| pmid = 9546223| title = Crystal structure of the type-2 Cu depleted laccase from Coprinus dnereus at 2.2 \u00c5 resolution| journal = Nature Structural Biology| volume = 5| issue = 4| pages = 310\u2013316| year = 1998| last1 = Ducros | first1 = V. R. | last2 = Brzozowski | first2 = A. M. | last3 = Wilson | first3 = K. S. | last4 = Brown | first4 = S. H. | last5 = \u00d8stergaard | first5 = P. | last6 = Schneider | first6 = P. | last7 = Yaver | first7 = D. S. | last8 = Pedersen | first8 = A. H. | last9 = Davies | first9 = G. J. \n}}</ref> in 1999 and has two daughters.<ref name=whoswho/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}{{FRS 2010}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Gideon John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of York]]\n[[Category:Members of the European Molecular Biology Organization]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n", "name_user": "Ysbl-scriptwriter", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated Prizes and Awards (Haworth Memorial,. iChem Global Energy, Queens Anniversary Award).  Added links.  Deleted expired Web group Page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gideon_Davies"}
{"title_page": "Belle Gibson", "text_new": "{{Short description|Cancer fraudster}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Belle Gibson\n| image         =\n| image_size    = 160px\n| alt           = Profile photo of Sabontu in head-scarf\n| caption       = Belle Gibson, Jan 2020\n| birth_name    = Annabelle Natalie Gibson\n| birth_date    = {{Birth-date and age|October 8, 1991}}<ref name=\"The Australian\"/><ref name=\"B&T\"/>\n| birth_place   = [[Launceston, Tasmania]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| home_town     = [[Northcote, Victoria]], Australia\n| nationality   = [[Australian people|Australian]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = Fabricated claims of having had multiple cancers which were self-treated through diet and alternative medicine.  Fabricated claims of undergoing multiple heart surgeries and suffering strokes.  Fraudulent claims that $300,000 of income from sales had been donated to charities.\n| partner       = Clive Rothwell\n| children      = 1\n}}\n\n'''Annabelle Natalie''' \"'''Belle'''\" '''Gibson''' (born October 8, 1991<ref name=\"The Australian\"/><ref name=\"B&T\">{{cite web|last1=Staff (B & T Magazine)|title='We Checked Belle\u2019s Birth Certificate' Women\u2019s Weekly Editor Helen McCabe Tells B&T|url=http://www.bandt.com.au/media/we-checked-belle-gibsons-birth-certificate-australian-womens-weekly-editor-helen-mccabe|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=June 30, 2015|quote=the magazine [Women's Wear Daily] has seen a birth certificate provided by her mother, Natalie, which clearly states she was born on October 8, 1991,}}</ref> in [[Launceston, Tasmania]], [[Australia]]) is a convicted [[Australian]] [[scammer]] and [[pseudoscience]] advocate. She is the author of ''The Whole Pantry'' [[mobile app]] and its later companion cookbook. Throughout her career as a wellness guru, Gibson claimed she had a diagnosis involving multiple [[cancer]] pathologies throughout her internal organs; claimed she had forgone modern science-based medical treatments; claimed she was effectively self-managing her multiple cancers through diet, exercise, and [[alternative medicine|alternative therapies]]; and claimed to have donated significant proportions of her income and her company's profits to numerous charities.\n\nIn March 2015, after reports identified Gibson's [[fraud]]ulent claims regarding her charitable giving, further media investigation revealed that she had also fabricated her stories of cancer, and had lied about her age, personal life and history. Concerns were expressed that Gibson had led a profligate lifestyle, renting an upmarket town house, leasing a luxury car and office space, undergoing cosmetic dental procedures, purchasing designer clothes and holidaying internationally, on money claimed to have been raised for charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/supporters-turn-on-belle-gibson-as-cancer-claims-unravel-20150313-1439ny.html|title=Supporters turn on Belle Gibson as cancer claims unravel|last=Toscano|first=Nick|last2=Donelly|first2=Beau|date=2015-03-14|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|language=en|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-224720/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/supporters-turn-on-belle-gibson-as-cancer-claims-unravel-20150313-1439ny.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> With a collapsing [[social media]] support base, Gibson admitted in an April 2015 interview that her claims of having multiple cancers had been fabricated, stating that \"none of it's true\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/diet-and-fitness/the-whole-pantry-author-belle-gibson-admits-she-lied-about-having-terminal-cancer-20150422-1mqt8a.html|title=The Whole Pantry author Belle Gibson admits she lied about having terminal cancer|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=22 April 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-224738/https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/health-and-wellness/the-whole-pantry-author-belle-gibson-admits-she-lied-about-having-terminal-cancer-20150422-1mqt8a.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|author2=Toscano, Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nGibson's actions were described as \"particularly predatory\"<ref name=\"sickness\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/29/jules-gibson-munchausen-by-internet-sickness-bloggers-fake-it-whole-pantry|title=M\u00fcnchausen by internet: the sickness bloggers who fake it online|last1=Montague|first1=Jules|date=30 April 2015|work=The Guardian Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922173756/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/29/jules-gibson-munchausen-by-internet-sickness-bloggers-fake-it-whole-pantry|archive-date=2018-09-22|publisher=Guardian News & Media Ltd}}</ref> and \"deceit on a grand scale, for personal profit\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tuohy|first1=Wendy|title=Belle Gibson: a story of deceit, betrayal of trust on a grand scale|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/belle-gibson-a-story-of-deceit-betrayal-of-trust-on-a-grand-scale/story-fni0fhk1-1227315495119|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref> On May 6, 2016, [[Consumer Affairs Victoria]] announced legal action against Gibson and Inkerman Road Nominees Pty Ltd (originally known as Belle Gibson Pty Ltd) for \"false claims by Ms. Gibson and her company concerning her diagnosis with terminal [[brain cancer]], her rejection of conventional cancer treatments in favour of natural remedies, and the donation of proceeds to various charities.\"<ref name=\"ConsumerAffairs2016\">{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson to face legal action over claims, Penguin agrees to enforceable undertaking - Media release|url=https://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/belle-gibson-to-face-legal-action-penguin-agrees-to-enforceable-undertaking--media-release|publisher=Consumer Affairs Victoria|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=6 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602184610/https://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/belle-gibson-to-face-legal-action-penguin-agrees-to-enforceable-undertaking--media-release|archive-date=2 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 15 March 2017, the [[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]] supported most of those claims, concluding that, \"Ms. Gibson had no reasonable basis to believe she had cancer.\"<ref name=\"judgement\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nAccording to interviews she has given, Belle Gibson left her [[Brisbane]] family home at age 12 to live with a classmate, and later lived with a family friend.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Whole Pantry founder inspires in the face of terminal cancer|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/the-whole-pantry-founder-inspires-in-the-face-of-terminal-cancer/story-fniym874-1227133426731|website=News.com.au|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=28 November 2014}}</ref> Gibson attended [[Wynnum State High School]] in [[Manly, Queensland|Manly]], [[Queensland]], until dropping out in Year 10,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/wellness-guru-belle-gibson-opposed-vaccination-backed-medical-cannabis/story-fnihsrf2-1227260568033 | title=Wellness guru Belle Gibson 'opposed vaccination, backed medical cannabis' | work=The Courier Mail | date=13 March 2015 | accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> although she also later claimed to have been [[homeschool]]ed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/cancer-survivor-belle-gibson-retains-lawyer-20150312-142ed2.html|title='Cancer survivor' Belle Gibson retains lawyer|last=Donelly|first=Beau|date=March 12, 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-223345/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/cancer-survivor-belle-gibson-retains-lawyer-20150312-142ed2.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> She worked for some time as a trainee for catering supply company PFD Food Services in [[Lytton, Queensland|Lytton]],<ref name = \"Psychopath\">{{cite news | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/mega-blogger-belle-gibson-described-herself-as-a-distinguished-psychopath/story-fni0fiyv-1227259174931 | title=Mega blogger Belle Gibson described herself as a 'distinguished psychopath' | work=The Courier Mail | date=12 March 2015 | accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> but [[social media]] reflected that by late 2008 she had relocated to [[Perth]], [[Western Australia]]. There, she was involved in the skateboarding culture and actively participated in its online community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skateboard.com.au/bandits/read.cfm?forum=15&thread=60945&p=2&archive=1|title=santa clause  Page 2|work=skateboard.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Back In Hospital - Round Three|url=http://www.skateboard.com.au/bandits/read.cfm?forum=15&thread=65113&archive=0&blog=0&p=1|website=skateboard.com.au|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref> Gibson subsequently moved from Perth to [[Melbourne]] in July 2009 and became a mother one year later, at age 18. Gibson launched ''The Whole Pantry'' [[mobile app]] in August 2013, at age 21.\n\nGibson reportedly told a prospective business partner in 2014 that she had \"[[Pseudonym|several names]]\" that she went under,<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/friends-and-doctors-raise-doubts-over-healing-belle-cancer-claims-20150310-1401rr.html|title=Friends and doctors raise doubts over 'Healing Belle' cancer claims|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=March 10, 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-220355/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/friends-and-doctors-raise-doubts-over-healing-belle-cancer-claims-20150310-1401rr.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax Media|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> and in her most recent interview with ''[[The Australian Women's Weekly]]'' claimed \"her mother changed her name five times\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Clair|title=What it's really like to interview Belle Gibson|url=http://www.aww.com.au/latest-news/in-the-mag/what-its-like-to-interview-belle-gibson-20282|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=The Australian Women's Weekly|publisher=Baeur Media}}</ref> Gibson's corporate filings indicate that she is three years younger than she publicly claims to be.<ref name=\"The Australian\"/>\n\n===''The Whole Pantry''===\nAfter Gibson launched ''The Whole Pantry'' app, it was reportedly downloaded 200,000 times within its first month. Gibson soon after signed a book deal with [[Lantern Books]], an imprint of [[Penguin Books]], for an accompanying table top [[cookbook]], which was published in October 2014. She further worked with [[Apple Inc.]] in September 2014 to transition the app as a privileged pre-installed default third party inclusion in the [[Apple Watch]]'s April 2015 launch.<ref name=\"auto\"/> By early 2015, it was estimated that in excess of $1 million had been made in sales of ''The Whole Pantry'' app and book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.com.au/news/zeitgeist/2015/3/what-we-know-about-belle-gibson/|title=Belle Gibson - The Whole Pantry|work=Elle}}</ref> Gibson chronicled her battle with [[cancer]] on a blog of the same name, but \"doubts about her claims surfaced after she failed to deliver a promised $300,000 donation to a charity\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mendham|first1=Tim|date=June 2015|title=Not Healthy|url=https://www.skeptics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/magazine/The%20Skeptic%20Volume%2035%20(2015)%20No%202.pdf|journal=The Skeptic|publisher=[[Australian Skeptics]]|volume=35|issue=2|page=9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226053715/https://www.skeptics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/magazine/The%20Skeptic%20Volume%2035%20(2015)%20No%202.pdf|archive-date=2017-02-26}}</ref>\n\nBefore doubts were raised about her health and charitable donation claims, Gibson had intended to expand her brand beyond the app, having earlier registered the [[Internet domain|domain]] ''The Whole Life'', and advertised in December 2014 to recruit an IT specialist to expand the app and brand portfolio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfh.io/jobs/952-ui-ux-designer-the-whole-pantry?hc_location=ufi|title=Remote Design Job - UI / UX Designer @ The Whole Pantry - WFH.io|work=wfh.io|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420174840/https://www.wfh.io/jobs/952-ui-ux-designer-the-whole-pantry?hc_location=ufi|archive-date=20 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Both ''The Whole Pantry'' app and ''The Whole Life'' were registered by Gibson's partner, Clive Rothwell, in her corporate name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://who.is/whois/thewholelife|title=Thewholelife.com Whois Lookup - Who.is - Who.is|work=who.is}}</ref>  The Whole Pantry registrar was amended in March 2015 after the controversy broke.<ref>{{cite web|title=TheWholePantryApp.Com|url=https://who.is/whois/thewholepantryapp|website=Who.Is|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile ''The Whole Pantry'' has unequivocally denied that Gibson ever helped anyone to reject conventional cancer treatment, Gibson has been quoted from her social media posts as claiming that she had \"countless times helped others\" to forgo conventional medical treatment for cancer and to treat themselves \"naturally\", as well as \"leading them down natural therapy for everything from fertility, depression, bone damage and other types of cancer\".<ref name=\"theage-backlash\" />\n\n===Health claims===\nIn interviews, Gibson claimed to have suffered from malignant brain, [[leukemia|blood]], [[splenic tumor|spleen]], [[endometrial cancer|uterine]], [[liver cancer|liver]], and [[kidney cancer|kidney]] cancers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/news/the-whole-pantry-withdrawn-holistic-recipe-book-taken-off-shelves-as-authors-cancer-claims-are-disputed-10114642.html|title=The Whole Pantry withdrawn: Holistic recipe book taken off shelves as Belle Gibson's cancer claims are disputed|work=The Independent}}</ref> which she attributed to a reaction to the [[Gardasil]] cervical cancer vaccine.<ref name = \"Psychopath\"/> When the book was launched in November 2014, Gibson claimed in its preface that she had been \"stable for two years now with no growth of the cancer\",<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\"/> but her story soon emerged as inconsistent: she also told media outlets that the cancer had reached her liver and kidneys, and three months earlier had posted on ''The Whole Pantry'''s [[Facebook]] page that her cancer had spread to her brain, blood, spleen, and uterus. She previously claimed that she had undergone [[heart surgery]] several times and to have momentarily died on the operating table. Gibson also claimed to have suffered a [[stroke]]. However, she was unable to substantiate her medical claims nor name the doctors who diagnosed and treated her. She also did not bear any surgical scars from her heart operations.<ref name=\"The Australian\" />\n\nGibson's and ''The Whole Pantry'''s statements regarding the benefits of exercise, healthy eating and a positive mindset were uncontroversial, being widely acknowledged as conducive to holistic well being. However, on her now-deleted [[Instagram]] account and in other social media, Gibson also promoted more controversial or potentially dangerous alternative medical practices, including [[Gerson therapy]],<ref name=\"fiction\"/> [[anti-vaccination]], and the consumption of non-pasteurised [[raw milk]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jefferson|first1=Andrew|last2=Cavanagh|first2=Rebekah|title=Lifestyle blogger Belle Gibson slips up on booze, milk|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/lifestyle-blogger-belle-gibson-slips-up-on-booze-milk/|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref>\n\nThe highly controversial Gerson therapy had been similarly promoted by another Australian wellness blogger, [[Jessica Ainscough]], whose funeral Gibson attended when Ainscough succumbed to cancer in late February 2015. With approximately 97% of the Australian population under seven years of age immunised, Federal [[vaccination policy]] heavily penalises parents who refuse to vaccinate their children, by denying access to significant welfare and other benefits, worth approximately $11,700 per annum. The sale of raw milk for human consumption is illegal in Australia and, in [[Victoria (state)|Victoria]], one three-year-old died and another four children under the age of five became seriously ill after consuming non-pasteurised milk in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Milman|first1=Oliver|title=Victoria launches crackdown on sale of 'raw' unpasteurised milk|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2014/dec/28/victoria-launches-crackdown-on-sale-of-raw-unpasteurised-milk|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Ltd}}</ref>\n\n===Charitable claims===\nAs Gibson's medical claims were being scrutinised, allegations emerged that charitable contributions raised in 2013 and 2014 had not been given to their intended causes.<ref name=\"theage-backlash\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/backlash-over-app-developer-belle-gibsons-missing-charity-money-20150309-13yzd4.html|title=Backlash over app developer Belle Gibson's missing charity money|last=Donelly|first=Beau|date=9 March 2015|work=The Age|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-213648/https://www.theage.com.au/technology/backlash-over-app-developer-belle-gibsons-missing-charity-money-20150309-13yzd4.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax Australia|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref name=\"essentialbaby\">{{cite news | url=http://www.essentialbaby.com.au/life-style/current-affairs/belle-gibson-the-missing-charity-money-and-the-confounding-cancer-claims-20150310-13zsel.html | title=Belle Gibson, the missing charity money and the confounding cancer claims | work=Essential Baby | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> Gibson denied the charges,<ref name=\"newscomau-refutes\">{{cite news | url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibsons-the-whole-pantry-refutes-claims-about-charity-donations/story-fniym3t1-1227255183760 | title=Belle Gibson's The Whole Pantry refutes claims about charity donations | work=news.com.au | date=10 March 2015 | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> but [[Fairfax Media]] revealed that she had \"failed to hand over proceeds solicited in the name of five charities\" and had \"grossly overstated the company's total donations to different causes\".<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\" /> Two charities confirmed to ''[[The Australian]]'' newspaper that Gibson's company had used their names in fundraising drives but had either failed to deliver the donations or had inadequately accounted for the funds.<ref name=\"erased\"/>\n\nGibson had claimed on a number of occasions in 2014 that ''The Whole Pantry'' had donated approximately $300,000 to charities, including maternal healthcare in developing nations, medical support for children with cancer, and funding schools in [[sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/macman/pop-into-the-pantry-app-for-a-healthier-lifestyle-20140723-ztvos.html|title=Pop into The Pantry app for a healthier lifestyle|last=Barker|first=Garry|date=July 17, 2014|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-213102/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/pop-into-the-pantry-app-for-a-healthier-lifestyle-20140717-ztvos.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> In late 2014, when ''The Whole Pantry'' app was pre-installed on the Apple [[iPad]], Gibson claimed through her Instagram account to be working with twenty different charities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson // thewholepantry@healing_belle|url=https://populagram.appspot.com/user/healing_belle|website=Populagram|publisher=Populgram, Instagram|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422174823/https://populagram.appspot.com/user/healing_belle|archive-date=22 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gibson has long claimed in her [[LinkedIn]] professional networking profile, established in February 2013, to be a [[philanthropist]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson, The Whole Pantry|url=https://au.linkedin.com/pub/belle-gibson/85/a97/686|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=30 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430210329/https://au.linkedin.com/pub/belle-gibson/85/a97/686|archive-date=30 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGibson eventually admitted, in relation to fraud proceedings, that she had seriously overstated the level of charitable contributions that had been made. Subsequent media reports in March 2015 revealed that it could only be ascertained that an estimated $7,000 of the previously claimed $300,000 had been donated to a total of three charities, with at least $1,000 of the $7,000 reportedly having been donated only after Gibson became aware of the Fairfax investigation into her earlier claims.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/charity-money-promised-by-inspirational-health-app-developer-belle-gibson-not-handed-over-20150308-13xgqk.html|title=Charity money promised by 'inspirational' health app developer Belle Gibson not handed over|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|last2=Toscano|first2=NIck|date=8 March 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-211226/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/charity-money-promised-by-inspirational-health-app-developer-belle-gibson-not-handed-over-20150306-13xgqk.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Another $1,000 of the $7,000 had been donated to a charitable cause under Rothwell's name, rather than Gibson's or the company name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://startsomegood.com/Venture/the_asrc_food_justice_truck/Supporters|title=Supporters - The ASRC Food Justice Truck - StartSomeGood: Igniting Ideas, Investment & Impact.|work=StartSomeGood|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420193743/http://startsomegood.com/Venture/the_asrc_food_justice_truck/Supporters|archive-date=20 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAlso in March 2015, the parents of a young child suffering from brain cancer, whom Gibson had befriended, came forward to report that they had been unaware that Gibson had earlier been claiming to be fundraising for their child's treatment on their behalf. The family had never received any funds from her or ''The Whole Pantry'', and suspected Gibson had been using information gleaned from the family's experiences to underpin her own claims to having brain cancer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cavanagh|first1=Rebekah|title=Family of desperately ill boy fear health guru Belle Gibson used their son to bolster her cancer claims|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/family-of-desperately-ill-boy-fear-health-guru-belle-gibson-used-their-son-to-bolster-her-cancer-claims/story-fni0fit3-1227273020233|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|publisher=[[Herald Sun]], [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]]|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Concern over publisher culpability===\nAs the controversy grew, questions began to be raised about Apple, Penguin and the Australian media's lack of due diligence in ''[[prima facie]]'' accepting Gibson's claims to suffering multiple cancers, an issue taken up by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]'s ''[[Media Watch (TV program)|Media Watch]]'' program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barry|first1=Paul|title=How the media fell for Belle|url=http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/s4198886.htm|website=ABC.NET.AU|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\nApple Inc., in response to media enquiry in March 2015, declined to remove ''The Whole Pantry'' app from sale, stating that it was only concerned about the functionality of the app. However, ''The Whole Pantry'' was soon thereafter removed from inclusion in the Apple Watch launch. Apple subsequently deleted the app from the Apple Store, and removed it from all Apple Watch promotional material. Apple has not provided any public comment regarding the reasons behind the removal of the app,<ref>{{cite news|last=Riley|first=Duncan|title=Fake cancer survivor Belle Gibson's app pulled from App Store, still linked to Apple Watch though|url=http://siliconangle.com/blog/2015/03/17/fake-cancer-survivor-belle-gibsons-app-pulled-from-app-store-still-linked-to-apple-watch-though/|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Siliconangle.com|publisher=SiliconANGLE Media|date=17 March 2015}}</ref> but an internal email from an Australian executive to the company's US office acknowledged that the removal would be subject to comment.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nLantern Books, when initially approached by investigative journalists, claimed it had not confirmed the validity of Gibson's cancer claims as it was not required for a cookbook.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hallbaeck|first1=Jan|title=The 'hole' in the pantry story: should Penguin have validated Belle Gibson's cancer claims?|url=https://theconversation.com/the-hole-in-the-pantry-story-should-penguin-have-validated-belle-gibsons-cancer-claims-38843|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=The Conversation|publisher=The Conversation Trust|date=16 March 2015}}</ref> Soon after, as the controversy grew, Penguin withdrew the book from sale, citing a lack of response from Gibson to its queries relating to the media accusations. However, Fairfax reported that Penguin had, prior to publication of the book, already quizzed and videotaped Gibson on her cancer story, as recounted in the [[preface]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/publisher-penguin-pulls-belle-gibson-cook-book-the-whole-pantry-20150316-1m0dsc.html|title=Publisher Penguin pulls Belle Gibson cook book The Whole Pantry|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=16 March 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2015.05.01-005533/http://www.smh.com.au/national/publisher-penguin-pulls-belle-gibson-cook-book-the-whole-pantry-20150316-1m0dsc.html|archive-date=2015-05-01|publisher=Fairfax Media|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> Penguin agreed to pay A$30,000 to the [[Consumer Affairs Victoria|Victorian Consumer Law Fund]] as a penalty for failing to validate the factual content of the book.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-36195825|title=Cancer-faking blogger faces legal action|date=2016-05-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n''[[Elle magazine|Elle Australia]]'' magazine, published by [[Bauer Media Group]], admitted that following a laudatory December 2014 story on Gibson, they had received but ultimately dismissed anonymous claims that she was fabricating her story.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lawrence|first1=Vanessa|title=What we know about Belle Gibson|url=http://www.elle.com.au/news/zeitgeist/2015/3/what-we-know-about-belle-gibson/|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Elle Australia|publisher=Elle Australia}}</ref> A second Bauer magazine, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', which had awarded Gibson its 2014 \"Fun Fearless Female\" social media award, admitted that it too had received and dismissed a similar email.<ref name=\"honest\" /> After Gibson's confessions, the magazine decided not to strip her of the award, stating that she had been \"reader nominated and reader voted.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sharp|first1=Annette|title=Cosmo defend failure to research Belle cancer claims and says she can keep Fun Fearless Female award|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/cosmo-defend-failure-to-research-belle-cancer-claims-and-says-she-can-keep-fun-fearless-female-award/story-fni0cvc9-1227318967969|accessdate=25 April 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=NewsCorp|date=24 April 2015}}</ref> However, a month earlier, ''Cosmopolitan''{{'}}s associate editor stated that they \"put forward the nomination myself\", indicating that the magazine {{ndash}} not the public {{ndash}} had been instrumental in promoting Gibson's award.<ref name=\"honest\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/health-lifestyle/lifestyle/2015/3/an-honest-account-of-our-experience-with-belle-gibson/|title=An honest account of our experience with Belle Gibson|last1=Sams|first1=Lauren|date=17 March 2015|work=Cosmopolitan Australia|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518091405/http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/health-lifestyle/lifestyle/2015/3/an-honest-account-of-our-experience-with-belle-gibson/|archive-date=18 May 2015|publisher=Bauer Media Group}}</ref>\n\nA conventional cancer research professional from the [[Garvan Institute of Medical Research]] also went public to state that, by failing to conduct basic [[fact checking]] and providing \"unfiltered [[public relations|PR]]\" to Gibson's untested claims, an uncritical media had been complicit in her \"scam\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burke|first1=Liz|title='They are all complicit': Cancer researcher Dr Darren Saunders slams Belle Gibson's 'enablers'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/they-are-all-complicit-cancer-researcher-dr-darren-saunders-slams-belle-gibsons-enablers/story-fneuzlbd-1227317296471|accessdate=23 April 2015|agency=News.com.au|publisher=News Limited}}</ref>\n\n===Erasing the story===\nOnce the controversy surfaced in the media, ''The Whole Pantry'' began removing any comments made on its (since deleted) Facebook page that questioned Gibson's claims, asserting that these comments only added to \"the misinformation\" of the initial Fairfax article. This selective deletion drew even more negative comment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryall|first1=Jenni|title=The mystery of Belle Gibson, who claimed she cured cancer with clean living|url=http://mashable.com/2015/03/29/belle-gibson-whole-pantry/|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Mashable Australia|publisher=Mashable Inc.}}</ref>\n\nSimultaneously, posts that Gibson had made on her Instagram account that made reference to her cancers or charitable donations were also selectively deleted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Does Belle Gibson Actually Have Cancer?|url=http://realitybasedmedicine.blogspot.com.au/2015/03/does-belle-gibson-actually-have-cancer.html|website=Reality Based Medicine|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref> Soon after, all posts were deleted from Gibson's and ''The Whole Pantry'''s Instagram accounts. Around the same time, individual postings about Gibson's cancer, and claims of having died briefly while under heart surgery, were also being selectively deleted by the administrator of her blog \"at the request of a user\".<ref name=\"erased\">{{cite news|last1=Guilliatt|first1=Richard|title=Whole Pantry founder Belle Gibson's stories of beating terminal cancer erased from internet|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/whole-pantry-founder-belle-gibsons-stories-of-beating-terminal-cancer-erased-from-internet/story-fni0fit3-1227257742137|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref> Accounts across a number of social media platforms were soon either abandoned, made private, or deleted in their entirety.<ref name=\"fiction\"/>{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nGibson subsequently established another Facebook account under the alias Harry Gibson, which was made private and used to hit back at Facebook followers questioning her claims or speaking to the media.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cavanagh|first1=Rebekah|last2=Tuohy|first2=Wendy|title=Belle Gibson slams 'fake cancer' claims in online rant|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/health-blogger-and-app-developer-belle-gibson-hits-back-at-bullying-critics-20150315-144g0v.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref>\n\n===Admission of deceit===\nIn late April 2015, Gibson gave an interview to ''The Australian Women's Weekly'', in which she admitted to having fabricated all her cancer claims. Gibson attributed her deceit to her upbringing, and specifically to [[child neglect|neglect]] by her now-[[Family estrangement|estranged]] mother, claiming to having been forced to take care of herself and her brother since the age of 5.<ref name=\"news.com.au\">{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Rebecca|title=Belle Gibson: 'No, None of it is true'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-no-none-of-it-is-true/story-fniym874-1227315232565|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=news.com.au|agency=News Limited}}</ref> The interview was, however, described as an admission of deceit, without expression of regret or apology.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Matt|title=Nothing to like about this pretty little liar|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/nothing-to-like-about-this-pretty-little-liar/story-fni0ffsx-1227320920457|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp Ltd|date=25 April 2015}}</ref> In a May 2015 interview with the same magazine, Gibson's mother Natalie Dal-Bello refuted several claims Gibson had made about her family, including the false claim that her brother was [[autism|autistic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson's mum slams troubled childhood claims as 'a lot of rubbish'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibsons-mum-slams-troubled-childhood-claims-as-a-lot-of-rubbish/story-fneuz9ev-1227358455303|accessdate=18 May 2015|work=news.com.au|agency=News Limited}}</ref> Gibson's ''Women's Weekly'' interview was arranged by [[Bespoke Approach]], and Gibson was provided ''[[pro bono]]'' representation by the company during the interview.<ref name=\"news.com.au\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/strewth/toil-for-the-belle/news-story/5be985d1f1b73c1a0fda7dab453ffab1|title=Toil for the Belle|last1=Jeffrey|first1=James|date=23 April 2015|work=The Australian|accessdate=25 April 2015|url-status=live|publisher=NewsCorp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Gibson was rumoured to have received A$45,000 for an interview with [[Nine Network]]'s ''[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/belle-gibson-promises-to-tell-the-whole-truth-i-have-lost-everything/news-story/dd6e5b8b3a31d7f13b7805214332e5a5|title=Belle Gibson promises to tell the whole truth: \u2018I have lost everything\u2019|last=Willis|first=Charlotte|date=2015-06-25|website=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Corp Australia|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003193353/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/belle-gibson-promises-to-tell-the-whole-truth-i-have-lost-everything/news-story/dd6e5b8b3a31d7f13b7805214332e5a5|archive-date=2017-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/broadcast/nine-network-faces-backlash-over-60-minutes-interview-with-belle-gibson/news-story/311065149cfe5289ea2b4d3af6ef283d|title=Nine Network faces backlash over 60 Minutes interview with Belle Gibson|last=Guilliatt|first=Richard|date=25 Jun 2015|work=The Australian|publisher=News Corp|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-date=|access-date=24 Jun 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legal action===\nConsumer Affairs Victoria brought legal action against Gibson for allegedly breaking Australian consumer law. The regulator said it had conducted an in-depth investigation of Gibson's activities and applied to Australia's Federal Court for leave to pursue legal action. Gibson's publisher, Penguin Australia, has already agreed to pay A$30,000 (US$22,200; \u00a315,300) to the Victorian Consumer Law Fund as a penalty for releasing The Whole Pantry, which was not fact checked.<ref name=\"ConsumerAffairs2016\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson: Australian blogger who faked cancer faces legal action|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-36195825|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2017, Federal Court Justice [[Debra Mortimer]] delivered the decision that \"most but not all\" of the claims were proven. Gibson did not appear in court for the decision. Justice Mortimer found that Gibson's claims had been misleading and deceptive, and that \"Ms. Gibson had no reasonable basis to believe she had cancer from the time she began making these claims in public to promote ''The Whole Pantry Book'' and the apps in mid-2013\", but there was not enough evidence to prove that she was not acting out of delusion.<ref name=\"judgement\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.9news.com.au/national/2017/03/15/06/22/belle-gibsons-judgement-to-be-handed-down-in-court|title=Disgraced wellness blogger Belle Gibson facing more than $1 million in fines|date=15 March 2017|work=9 News|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref><ref name=\"2017 FCA 240\">{{cite AustLII|FCA|240|2017|litigants=Director of Consumer Affairs Victoria v Gibson |date=15 March 2017 |courtname=[[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]]}}.</ref><ref name=\"fad\"/>\n\nIn September 2017, Gibson was fined A$410,000 (US$310,000; \u00a3240,000) for making false claims about her donations to charity.<ref name=\"2017 FCA 1148\">{{cite AustLII|FCA|1148|2017|litigants=Director of Consumer Affairs Victoria v Gibson (No 3) |date=28 September 2017 |courtname=[[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]]}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Karen |last=Percy |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-28/disgraced-wellness-blogger-belle-gibson-fined/8995500 |title=Fake wellness blogger Belle Gibson fined over cancer claims |date=28 September 2017 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission}}</ref> {{As of|2019|04}}, Gibson had not yet paid the fine, and authorities were seeking power to charge her with [[contempt of court]]. A new trial was set for 14 May  and she faced an undetermined number of years in jail if she did not attend.<ref>{{cite news |title=Belle Gibson faces jail time if $410k fine for cancer fraud goes unpaid |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-27/belle-gibson-faces-jail-term-for-unpaid-cancer-fraud-fine/10558150 |date=28 November 2018 |access-date=28 November 2018 |last=Oaten |first=James |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson to explain why she hasn\u2019t paid $410k fine for duping sick Aussies|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/belle-gibson-to-explain-why-she-hasnt-paid-410k-fine-for-duping-sick-aussies/news-story/43c24e05cb91d5b6f74f3aa2e26b392c|date=17 April 2019|access-date=18 April 2019|publisher=news.com.au}}</ref> As of mid-September 2019, Gibson still had not paid, claiming to be broke, and Consumer Affairs Victoria were still seeking to enforce the penalty.<ref>\"Belle Gibson 'in hiding'\". The Daily Telegraph (Australia), 15 Sep 2019, p. 11</ref> In a 2017 letter later released by the Federal Court, Gibson had stated that she was $170,000 in debt, and had $5,000 to her name.<ref name=\"letter\" />\n\n==House raid by police==\nOn 22 January 2020, the Sheriff\u2019s Office of Victoria  raided Gibson's home in Northcote and seized items to recoup Gibson's unpaid fines,<ref name=\"raided\"/> which, due to interest and costs, exceeded half a million dollars.<ref name=\"sheriff\"/>\n\n==Claimed adoption into Oromo community==\nOn 23 January 2020, a Shabo Media video from October 2019 surfaced in which Gibson was wearing a headscarf and speaking partially in [[Oromo language]] (referring to herself as \"Sanbotu\"), discussing the political situation in [[Ethiopia]] with an interviewer and referring to Ethiopia as \"back home\". She professed to have been adopted by the Ethiopian community in Melbourne after volunteering for four years, calling the adoption a gift from \"Allah\".<ref name=\"adopted\"/><ref name=\"community\"/>\n\nHowever, on the same day, the president of the Australian Oromo Community Association in Victoria, Tarekegn Chimdi, stated that Gibson was not a registered volunteer, \"is not a community member and she\u2019s also not working with the community,\" and that he had only seen her at events two or three times. He expressed that nobody seemed to know who she was and he had only just learnt of her backstory, and expressed a desire for her to stop saying she is part of the community.<ref name=\"rejected\"/><ref name=\"Melbourne\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ashley Kirilow]], a Canadian fraudster who raised money for cancer charities by falsely claiming that she had cancer\n*[[Michael Guglielmucci]], an Australian singer who claimed to have cancer to boost his performing career\n*[[Diet and cancer]]\n*[[Munchausen syndrome]] <ref name=\"sickness\"/><ref name=\"munchausen\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"fiction\">{{cite news|last1=Debelle|first1=Penelope|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-and-the-whole-pantry-is-her-story-fact-or-fiction/story-fni0dguy-1227265261138|title=Belle Gibson and The Whole Pantry: Is her story fact or fiction?|date=2015-03-16|work=The Advertiser|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419125643/https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-and-the-whole-pantry-is-her-story-fact-or-fiction/news-story/e2470157576603c9d0f1743b6e238ebd|archive-date=2020-04-19|publisher=News Corp|last2=Hadfield|first2=Shelley|location=Adelaide, SA}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"letter\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/finance/money/wealth/2017-letter-belle-gibson-wrote-detailing-debts-released/news-story/1a9eb9b29b181fda21340c873a92cf0e|title=2017 letter Belle Gibson wrote detailing debts released|date=2020-02-18|work=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Pty Ltd|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301050632/https://www.news.com.au/finance/money/wealth/2017-letter-belle-gibson-wrote-detailing-debts-released/news-story/1a9eb9b29b181fda21340c873a92cf0e|archive-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"munchausen\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/munchausen-syndrome-why-bloggers-like-cancer-fraud-belle-gibson-fake-sickness-online-10215185.html|title=Munchausen syndrome: Why bloggers like cancer fraud Belle Gibson fake sickness online|last=Nianias|first=Helen|date=2015-04-30|work=The Independent|publisher=Independent Digital News & Media Ltd|location=UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428224900/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/munchausen-syndrome-why-bloggers-like-cancer-fraud-belle-gibson-fake-sickness-online-10215185.html|archive-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Melbourne\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/belle-gibson-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community-in-melbourne/news-story/faef622ee9d2b5bee4e4a9518420c315|title=Belle Gibson has been adopted by Ethiopian community in Melbourne|last=Smith|first=Rohan|date=2020-01-24|work=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Pty Ltd|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126195951/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/belle-gibson-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community-in-melbourne/news-story/faef622ee9d2b5bee4e4a9518420c315|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"fad\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/belle-gibson-backs-new-health-fad-ahead-of-court-judgment/news-story/d5850eb9a6c9c4c3e4420141c2a42f6a|title=Belle Gibson backs new health fad ahead of court judgment|last=Cavanagh|first=Rebekah|date=15 March 2017|work=Herald Sun|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-125528/https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/belle-gibson-backs-new-health-fad-ahead-of-court-judgment/news-story/d5850eb9a6c9c4c3e4420141c2a42f6a|archive-date=2020-02-01|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"community\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/belle-gibson-says-she-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/11895252|title=Belle Gibson 'adopted' by Ethiopian community|last=Kinsella|first=Elise|date=2020-01-23|work=ABC News|location=Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126203125/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/belle-gibson-says-she-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/11895252|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/business/apple-exposed-over-belle-gibson-affair-20171119-gzoasp.html|title=Apple exposed over Belle Gibson affair|last1=Toscano|first1=Nick|date=19 November 2017|work=The Age|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-223125/https://www.theage.com.au/business/apple-exposed-over-belle-gibson-affair-20171119-gzoasp.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|last2=Donelly|first2=Beau|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"The Australian\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/mega-blogger-belle-gibson-casts-doubt-on-her-own-cancer-claims/story-e6frg8zx-1227255933051|title=Mega-blogger Belle Gibson casts doubt on her own cancer claims|last1=Guilliatt|first1=Richard|date=10 March 2015|newspaper=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/2017.01.26-011131/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/megablogger-belle-gibson-casts-doubt-on-her-own-cancer-claims/news-story/de179f2f17de51d1071096eb7bd2bdee|archive-date=2017-01-26|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rejected\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibson-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/news-story/7947e2e0c3ef96814e3d1352605b61e2|title=Cancer fraudster rejected by Ethiopians|last=Akerman|first=Tessa|date=24 January 2020|work=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-132450/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibson-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/news-story/7947e2e0c3ef96814e3d1352605b61e2|archive-date=2020-02-01|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"adopted\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/people-entertainment/2020/01/23/belle-gibson-ethiopian-oromo/|title=Cancer fraudster Belle Gibson \u2018adopted\u2019 by Ethiopian community|date=January 23, 2020|work=The New Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123132020/https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/people-entertainment/2020/01/23/belle-gibson-ethiopian-oromo/|archive-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sheriff\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/people/2020/01/22/belle-gibson-cancer-sheriff-fine/|title=Sheriff raids cancer fraudster Belle Gibson's home over unpaid fine|last=AAP|date=2020-01-22|work=The New Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122215711/https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/people/2020/01/22/belle-gibson-cancer-sheriff-fine/|archive-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"raided\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibsons-home-raided-by-sheriff-over-cancer-fraud/news-story/5d016d637d8f73a0756afe77d301920c|title=Belle Gibson\u2019s home raided by sheriff over cancer fraud fine|last=Urban|first=Rebecca|date=2020-01-22|work=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-210004/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibsons-home-raided-by-sheriff-over-cancer-fraud/news-story/5d016d637d8f73a0756afe77d301920c|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150314032024/http://thewholepantryapp.com/ The Whole Pantry website], registered by Gibson\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Belle}}\n[[Category:Australian fraudsters]]\n[[Category:Health fraud]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:People from Launceston, Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscientific diet advocates]]\n[[Category:Alternative cancer treatment advocates]]\n[[Category:Confidence tricksters]]\n[[Category:Medical controversies in Australia]]\n[[Category:People convicted for health fraud]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Cancer fraudster}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Belle Gibson\n| image         =\n| image_size    = 160px\n| alt           = Profile photo of Sabontu in head-scarf\n| caption       = Belle Gibson, Jan 2020\n| birth_name    = Annabelle Natalie Gibson\n| birth_date    = {{Birth-date and age|October 8, 1991}}<ref name=\"The Australian\"/><ref name=\"B&T\"/>\n| birth_place   = [[Launceston, Tasmania]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| home_town     = [[Northcote, Victoria]], Australia\n| nationality   = [[Australian people|Australian]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = Fabricated claims of having had multiple cancers which were self-treated through diet and alternative medicine.  Fabricated claims of undergoing multiple heart surgeries and suffering strokes.  Fraudulent claims that $300,000 of income from sales had been donated to charities.\n| partner       = Clive Rothwell\n| children      = 1\n}}\n\n'''Annabelle Natalie''' \"'''Belle'''\" '''Gibson''' (born October 8, 1991<ref name=\"The Australian\"/><ref name=\"B&T\">{{cite web|last1=Staff (B & T Magazine)|title='We Checked Belle\u2019s Birth Certificate' Women\u2019s Weekly Editor Helen McCabe Tells B&T|url=http://www.bandt.com.au/media/we-checked-belle-gibsons-birth-certificate-australian-womens-weekly-editor-helen-mccabe|accessdate=January 14, 2018|date=June 30, 2015|quote=the magazine [Women's Wear Daily] has seen a birth certificate provided by her mother, Natalie, which clearly states she was born on October 8, 1991,}}</ref> in [[Launceston, Tasmania]], [[Australia]]) is a convicted [[Australian]] [[scammer]] and [[pseudoscience]] advocate. She is the author of ''The Whole Pantry'' [[mobile app]] and its later companion cookbook. Throughout her career as a wellness guru, Gibson claimed she had a diagnosis involving multiple [[cancer]] pathologies throughout her internal organs; claimed she had forgone modern science-based medical treatments; claimed she was effectively self-managing her multiple cancers through diet, exercise, and [[alternative medicine|alternative therapies]]; and claimed to have donated significant proportions of her income and her company's profits to numerous charities.\n\nIn March 2015, after reports identified Gibson's [[fraud]]ulent claims regarding her charitable giving, further media investigation revealed that she had also fabricated her stories of cancer, and had lied about her age, personal life and history. Concerns were expressed that Gibson had led a profligate lifestyle, renting an upmarket town house, leasing a luxury car and office space, undergoing cosmetic dental procedures, purchasing designer clothes and holidaying internationally, on money claimed to have been raised for charity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/supporters-turn-on-belle-gibson-as-cancer-claims-unravel-20150313-1439ny.html|title=Supporters turn on Belle Gibson as cancer claims unravel|last=Toscano|first=Nick|last2=Donelly|first2=Beau|date=2015-03-14|website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|language=en|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-224720/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/supporters-turn-on-belle-gibson-as-cancer-claims-unravel-20150313-1439ny.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> With a collapsing [[social media]] support base, Gibson admitted in an April 2015 interview that her claims of having multiple cancers had been fabricated, stating that \"none of it's true\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/diet-and-fitness/the-whole-pantry-author-belle-gibson-admits-she-lied-about-having-terminal-cancer-20150422-1mqt8a.html|title=The Whole Pantry author Belle Gibson admits she lied about having terminal cancer|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=22 April 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-224738/https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/health-and-wellness/the-whole-pantry-author-belle-gibson-admits-she-lied-about-having-terminal-cancer-20150422-1mqt8a.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|author2=Toscano, Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nGibson's actions were described as \"particularly predatory\"<ref name=\"sickness\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/29/jules-gibson-munchausen-by-internet-sickness-bloggers-fake-it-whole-pantry|title=M\u00fcnchausen by internet: the sickness bloggers who fake it online|last1=Montague|first1=Jules|date=30 April 2015|work=The Guardian Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922173756/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/apr/29/jules-gibson-munchausen-by-internet-sickness-bloggers-fake-it-whole-pantry|archive-date=2018-09-22|publisher=Guardian News & Media Ltd}}</ref> and \"deceit on a grand scale, for personal profit\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tuohy|first1=Wendy|title=Belle Gibson: a story of deceit, betrayal of trust on a grand scale|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/belle-gibson-a-story-of-deceit-betrayal-of-trust-on-a-grand-scale/story-fni0fhk1-1227315495119|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref> On May 6, 2016, [[Consumer Affairs Victoria]] announced legal action against Gibson and Inkerman Road Nominees Pty Ltd (originally known as Belle Gibson Pty Ltd) for \"false claims by Ms. Gibson and her company concerning her diagnosis with terminal [[brain cancer]], her rejection of conventional cancer treatments in favour of natural remedies, and the donation of proceeds to various charities.\"<ref name=\"ConsumerAffairs2016\">{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson to face legal action over claims, Penguin agrees to enforceable undertaking - Media release|url=https://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/belle-gibson-to-face-legal-action-penguin-agrees-to-enforceable-undertaking--media-release|publisher=Consumer Affairs Victoria|accessdate=16 May 2016|date=6 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602184610/https://www.consumer.vic.gov.au/news-and-events/media-releases/belle-gibson-to-face-legal-action-penguin-agrees-to-enforceable-undertaking--media-release|archive-date=2 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 15 March 2017, the [[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]] supported most of those claims, concluding that, \"Ms. Gibson had no reasonable basis to believe she had cancer.\"<ref name=\"judgement\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nAccording to interviews she has given, Belle Gibson left her [[Brisbane]] family home at age 12 to live with a classmate, and later lived with a family friend.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Whole Pantry founder inspires in the face of terminal cancer|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/the-whole-pantry-founder-inspires-in-the-face-of-terminal-cancer/story-fniym874-1227133426731|website=News.com.au|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=28 November 2014}}</ref> Gibson attended [[Wynnum State High School]] in [[Manly, Queensland|Manly]], [[Queensland]], until dropping out in Year 10,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/wellness-guru-belle-gibson-opposed-vaccination-backed-medical-cannabis/story-fnihsrf2-1227260568033 | title=Wellness guru Belle Gibson 'opposed vaccination, backed medical cannabis' | work=The Courier Mail | date=13 March 2015 | accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> although she also later claimed to have been [[homeschool]]ed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/cancer-survivor-belle-gibson-retains-lawyer-20150312-142ed2.html|title='Cancer survivor' Belle Gibson retains lawyer|last=Donelly|first=Beau|date=March 12, 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-223345/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/cancer-survivor-belle-gibson-retains-lawyer-20150312-142ed2.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> She worked for some time as a trainee for catering supply company PFD Food Services in [[Lytton, Queensland|Lytton]],<ref name = \"Psychopath\">{{cite news | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/mega-blogger-belle-gibson-described-herself-as-a-distinguished-psychopath/story-fni0fiyv-1227259174931 | title=Mega blogger Belle Gibson described herself as a 'distinguished psychopath' | work=The Courier Mail | date=12 March 2015 | accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref> but [[social media]] reflected that by late 2008 she had relocated to [[Perth]], [[Western Australia]]. There, she was involved in the skateboarding culture and actively participated in its online community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skateboard.com.au/bandits/read.cfm?forum=15&thread=60945&p=2&archive=1|title=santa clause  Page 2|work=skateboard.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Back In Hospital - Round Three|url=http://www.skateboard.com.au/bandits/read.cfm?forum=15&thread=65113&archive=0&blog=0&p=1|website=skateboard.com.au|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref> Gibson subsequently moved from Perth to [[Melbourne]] in July 2009 and became a mother one year later, at age 18. Gibson launched ''The Whole Pantry'' [[mobile app]] in August 2013, at age 21.\n\nGibson reportedly told a prospective business partner in 2014 that she had \"[[Pseudonym|several names]]\" that she went under,<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/friends-and-doctors-raise-doubts-over-healing-belle-cancer-claims-20150310-1401rr.html|title=Friends and doctors raise doubts over 'Healing Belle' cancer claims|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=March 10, 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-220355/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/friends-and-doctors-raise-doubts-over-healing-belle-cancer-claims-20150310-1401rr.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax Media|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> and in her most recent interview with ''[[The Australian Women's Weekly]]'' claimed \"her mother changed her name five times\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Clair|title=What it's really like to interview Belle Gibson|url=http://www.aww.com.au/latest-news/in-the-mag/what-its-like-to-interview-belle-gibson-20282|accessdate=22 April 2015|newspaper=The Australian Women's Weekly|publisher=Baeur Media}}</ref> Gibson's corporate filings indicate that she is three years younger than she publicly claims to be.<ref name=\"The Australian\"/>\n\n===''The Whole Pantry''===\nAfter Gibson launched ''The Whole Pantry'' app, it was reportedly downloaded 200,000 times within its first month. Gibson soon after signed a book deal with [[Lantern Books]], an imprint of [[Penguin Books]], for an accompanying table top [[cookbook]], which was published in October 2014. She further worked with [[Apple Inc.]] in September 2014 to transition the app as a privileged pre-installed default third party inclusion in the [[Apple Watch]]'s April 2015 launch.<ref name=\"auto\"/> By early 2015, it was estimated that in excess of $1 million had been made in sales of ''The Whole Pantry'' app and book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elle.com.au/news/zeitgeist/2015/3/what-we-know-about-belle-gibson/|title=Belle Gibson - The Whole Pantry|work=Elle}}</ref> Gibson chronicled her battle with [[cancer]] on a blog of the same name, but \"doubts about her claims surfaced after she failed to deliver a promised $300,000 donation to a charity\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mendham|first1=Tim|date=June 2015|title=Not Healthy|url=https://www.skeptics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/magazine/The%20Skeptic%20Volume%2035%20(2015)%20No%202.pdf|journal=The Skeptic|publisher=[[Australian Skeptics]]|volume=35|issue=2|page=9|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226053715/https://www.skeptics.com.au/wp-content/uploads/magazine/The%20Skeptic%20Volume%2035%20(2015)%20No%202.pdf|archive-date=2017-02-26}}</ref>\n\nBefore doubts were raised about her health and charitable donation claims, Gibson had intended to expand her brand beyond the app, having earlier registered the [[Internet domain|domain]] ''The Whole Life'', and advertised in December 2014 to recruit an IT specialist to expand the app and brand portfolio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfh.io/jobs/952-ui-ux-designer-the-whole-pantry?hc_location=ufi|title=Remote Design Job - UI / UX Designer @ The Whole Pantry - WFH.io|work=wfh.io|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420174840/https://www.wfh.io/jobs/952-ui-ux-designer-the-whole-pantry?hc_location=ufi|archive-date=20 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Both ''The Whole Pantry'' app and ''The Whole Life'' were registered by Gibson's partner, Clive Rothwell, in her corporate name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://who.is/whois/thewholelife|title=Thewholelife.com Whois Lookup - Who.is - Who.is|work=who.is}}</ref>  The Whole Pantry registrar was amended in March 2015 after the controversy broke.<ref>{{cite web|title=TheWholePantryApp.Com|url=https://who.is/whois/thewholepantryapp|website=Who.Is|accessdate=23 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile ''The Whole Pantry'' has unequivocally denied that Gibson ever helped anyone to reject conventional cancer treatment, Gibson has been quoted from her social media posts as claiming that she had \"countless times helped others\" to forgo conventional medical treatment for cancer and to treat themselves \"naturally\", as well as \"leading them down natural therapy for everything from fertility, depression, bone damage and other types of cancer\".<ref name=\"theage-backlash\" />\n\n===Health claims===\nIn interviews, Gibson claimed to have suffered from malignant brain, [[leukemia|blood]], [[splenic tumor|spleen]], [[endometrial cancer|uterine]], [[liver cancer|liver]], and [[kidney cancer|kidney]] cancers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/news/the-whole-pantry-withdrawn-holistic-recipe-book-taken-off-shelves-as-authors-cancer-claims-are-disputed-10114642.html|title=The Whole Pantry withdrawn: Holistic recipe book taken off shelves as Belle Gibson's cancer claims are disputed|work=The Independent}}</ref> which she attributed to a reaction to the [[Gardasil]] cervical cancer vaccine.<ref name = \"Psychopath\"/> When the book was launched in November 2014, Gibson claimed in its preface that she had been \"stable for two years now with no growth of the cancer\",<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\"/> but her story soon emerged as inconsistent: she also told media outlets that the cancer had reached her liver and kidneys, and three months earlier had posted on ''The Whole Pantry'''s [[Facebook]] page that her cancer had spread to her brain, blood, spleen, and uterus. She previously claimed that she had undergone [[heart surgery]] several times and to have momentarily died on the operating table. Gibson also claimed to have suffered a [[stroke]]. However, she was unable to substantiate her medical claims nor name the doctors who diagnosed and treated her. She also did not bear any surgical scars from her heart operations.<ref name=\"The Australian\" />\n\nGibson's and ''The Whole Pantry'''s statements regarding the benefits of exercise, healthy eating and a positive mindset were uncontroversial, being widely acknowledged as conducive to holistic well being. However, on her now-deleted [[Instagram]] account and in other social media, Gibson also promoted more controversial or potentially dangerous alternative medical practices, including [[Gerson therapy]],<ref name=\"fiction\"> [[anti-vaccination]], and the consumption of non-pasteurised [[raw milk]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jefferson|first1=Andrew|last2=Cavanagh|first2=Rebekah|title=Lifestyle blogger Belle Gibson slips up on booze, milk|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/lifestyle-blogger-belle-gibson-slips-up-on-booze-milk/|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref>\n\nThe highly controversial Gerson therapy had been similarly promoted by another Australian wellness blogger, [[Jessica Ainscough]], whose funeral Gibson attended when Ainscough succumbed to cancer in late February 2015. With approximately 97% of the Australian population under seven years of age immunised, Federal [[vaccination policy]] heavily penalises parents who refuse to vaccinate their children, by denying access to significant welfare and other benefits, worth approximately $11,700 per annum. The sale of raw milk for human consumption is illegal in Australia and, in [[Victoria (state)|Victoria]], one three-year-old died and another four children under the age of five became seriously ill after consuming non-pasteurised milk in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Milman|first1=Oliver|title=Victoria launches crackdown on sale of 'raw' unpasteurised milk|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2014/dec/28/victoria-launches-crackdown-on-sale-of-raw-unpasteurised-milk|accessdate=23 April 2015|work=The Guardian|publisher=Guardian News and Media Ltd}}</ref>\n\n===Charitable claims===\nAs Gibson's medical claims were being scrutinised, allegations emerged that charitable contributions raised in 2013 and 2014 had not been given to their intended causes.<ref name=\"theage-backlash\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/backlash-over-app-developer-belle-gibsons-missing-charity-money-20150309-13yzd4.html|title=Backlash over app developer Belle Gibson's missing charity money|last=Donelly|first=Beau|date=9 March 2015|work=The Age|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-213648/https://www.theage.com.au/technology/backlash-over-app-developer-belle-gibsons-missing-charity-money-20150309-13yzd4.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax Australia|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref name=\"essentialbaby\">{{cite news | url=http://www.essentialbaby.com.au/life-style/current-affairs/belle-gibson-the-missing-charity-money-and-the-confounding-cancer-claims-20150310-13zsel.html | title=Belle Gibson, the missing charity money and the confounding cancer claims | work=Essential Baby | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> Gibson denied the charges,<ref name=\"newscomau-refutes\">{{cite news | url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibsons-the-whole-pantry-refutes-claims-about-charity-donations/story-fniym3t1-1227255183760 | title=Belle Gibson's The Whole Pantry refutes claims about charity donations | work=news.com.au | date=10 March 2015 | accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> but [[Fairfax Media]] revealed that she had \"failed to hand over proceeds solicited in the name of five charities\" and had \"grossly overstated the company's total donations to different causes\".<ref name=\"smh-healingbelle\" /> Two charities confirmed to ''[[The Australian]]'' newspaper that Gibson's company had used their names in fundraising drives but had either failed to deliver the donations or had inadequately accounted for the funds.<ref name=\"erased\"/>\n\nGibson had claimed on a number of occasions in 2014 that ''The Whole Pantry'' had donated approximately $300,000 to charities, including maternal healthcare in developing nations, medical support for children with cancer, and funding schools in [[sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/macman/pop-into-the-pantry-app-for-a-healthier-lifestyle-20140723-ztvos.html|title=Pop into The Pantry app for a healthier lifestyle|last=Barker|first=Garry|date=July 17, 2014|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-213102/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/pop-into-the-pantry-app-for-a-healthier-lifestyle-20140717-ztvos.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> In late 2014, when ''The Whole Pantry'' app was pre-installed on the Apple [[iPad]], Gibson claimed through her Instagram account to be working with twenty different charities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson // thewholepantry@healing_belle|url=https://populagram.appspot.com/user/healing_belle|website=Populagram|publisher=Populgram, Instagram|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422174823/https://populagram.appspot.com/user/healing_belle|archive-date=22 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gibson has long claimed in her [[LinkedIn]] professional networking profile, established in February 2013, to be a [[philanthropist]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Belle Gibson, The Whole Pantry|url=https://au.linkedin.com/pub/belle-gibson/85/a97/686|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=30 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430210329/https://au.linkedin.com/pub/belle-gibson/85/a97/686|archive-date=30 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGibson eventually admitted, in relation to fraud proceedings, that she had seriously overstated the level of charitable contributions that had been made. Subsequent media reports in March 2015 revealed that it could only be ascertained that an estimated $7,000 of the previously claimed $300,000 had been donated to a total of three charities, with at least $1,000 of the $7,000 reportedly having been donated only after Gibson became aware of the Fairfax investigation into her earlier claims.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/charity-money-promised-by-inspirational-health-app-developer-belle-gibson-not-handed-over-20150308-13xgqk.html|title=Charity money promised by 'inspirational' health app developer Belle Gibson not handed over|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|last2=Toscano|first2=NIck|date=8 March 2015|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax|url-access=registration|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2020.01.24-211226/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/charity-money-promised-by-inspirational-health-app-developer-belle-gibson-not-handed-over-20150306-13xgqk.html|archive-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> Another $1,000 of the $7,000 had been donated to a charitable cause under Rothwell's name, rather than Gibson's or the company name.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://startsomegood.com/Venture/the_asrc_food_justice_truck/Supporters|title=Supporters - The ASRC Food Justice Truck - StartSomeGood: Igniting Ideas, Investment & Impact.|work=StartSomeGood|access-date=20 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420193743/http://startsomegood.com/Venture/the_asrc_food_justice_truck/Supporters|archive-date=20 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAlso in March 2015, the parents of a young child suffering from brain cancer, whom Gibson had befriended, came forward to report that they had been unaware that Gibson had earlier been claiming to be fundraising for their child's treatment on their behalf. The family had never received any funds from her or ''The Whole Pantry'', and suspected Gibson had been using information gleaned from the family's experiences to underpin her own claims to having brain cancer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cavanagh|first1=Rebekah|title=Family of desperately ill boy fear health guru Belle Gibson used their son to bolster her cancer claims|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/family-of-desperately-ill-boy-fear-health-guru-belle-gibson-used-their-son-to-bolster-her-cancer-claims/story-fni0fit3-1227273020233|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|publisher=[[Herald Sun]], [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]]|accessdate=20 April 2015|date=21 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Concern over publisher culpability===\nAs the controversy grew, questions began to be raised about Apple, Penguin and the Australian media's lack of due diligence in ''[[prima facie]]'' accepting Gibson's claims to suffering multiple cancers, an issue taken up by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]]'s ''[[Media Watch (TV program)|Media Watch]]'' program.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barry|first1=Paul|title=How the media fell for Belle|url=http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/s4198886.htm|website=ABC.NET.AU|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\nApple Inc., in response to media enquiry in March 2015, declined to remove ''The Whole Pantry'' app from sale, stating that it was only concerned about the functionality of the app. However, ''The Whole Pantry'' was soon thereafter removed from inclusion in the Apple Watch launch. Apple subsequently deleted the app from the Apple Store, and removed it from all Apple Watch promotional material. Apple has not provided any public comment regarding the reasons behind the removal of the app,<ref>{{cite news|last=Riley|first=Duncan|title=Fake cancer survivor Belle Gibson's app pulled from App Store, still linked to Apple Watch though|url=http://siliconangle.com/blog/2015/03/17/fake-cancer-survivor-belle-gibsons-app-pulled-from-app-store-still-linked-to-apple-watch-though/|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Siliconangle.com|publisher=SiliconANGLE Media|date=17 March 2015}}</ref> but an internal email from an Australian executive to the company's US office acknowledged that the removal would be subject to comment.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nLantern Books, when initially approached by investigative journalists, claimed it had not confirmed the validity of Gibson's cancer claims as it was not required for a cookbook.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hallbaeck|first1=Jan|title=The 'hole' in the pantry story: should Penguin have validated Belle Gibson's cancer claims?|url=https://theconversation.com/the-hole-in-the-pantry-story-should-penguin-have-validated-belle-gibsons-cancer-claims-38843|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=The Conversation|publisher=The Conversation Trust|date=16 March 2015}}</ref> Soon after, as the controversy grew, Penguin withdrew the book from sale, citing a lack of response from Gibson to its queries relating to the media accusations. However, Fairfax reported that Penguin had, prior to publication of the book, already quizzed and videotaped Gibson on her cancer story, as recounted in the [[preface]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/publisher-penguin-pulls-belle-gibson-cook-book-the-whole-pantry-20150316-1m0dsc.html|title=Publisher Penguin pulls Belle Gibson cook book The Whole Pantry|last1=Donelly|first1=Beau|date=16 March 2015|work=Sydney Morning Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2015.05.01-005533/http://www.smh.com.au/national/publisher-penguin-pulls-belle-gibson-cook-book-the-whole-pantry-20150316-1m0dsc.html|archive-date=2015-05-01|publisher=Fairfax Media|last2=Toscano|first2=Nick|url-access=registration}}</ref> Penguin agreed to pay A$30,000 to the [[Consumer Affairs Victoria|Victorian Consumer Law Fund]] as a penalty for failing to validate the factual content of the book.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-36195825|title=Cancer-faking blogger faces legal action|date=2016-05-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-10-04|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n''[[Elle magazine|Elle Australia]]'' magazine, published by [[Bauer Media Group]], admitted that following a laudatory December 2014 story on Gibson, they had received but ultimately dismissed anonymous claims that she was fabricating her story.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lawrence|first1=Vanessa|title=What we know about Belle Gibson|url=http://www.elle.com.au/news/zeitgeist/2015/3/what-we-know-about-belle-gibson/|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Elle Australia|publisher=Elle Australia}}</ref> A second Bauer magazine, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', which had awarded Gibson its 2014 \"Fun Fearless Female\" social media award, admitted that it too had received and dismissed a similar email.<ref name=\"honest\" /> After Gibson's confessions, the magazine decided not to strip her of the award, stating that she had been \"reader nominated and reader voted.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sharp|first1=Annette|title=Cosmo defend failure to research Belle cancer claims and says she can keep Fun Fearless Female award|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/cosmo-defend-failure-to-research-belle-cancer-claims-and-says-she-can-keep-fun-fearless-female-award/story-fni0cvc9-1227318967969|accessdate=25 April 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=NewsCorp|date=24 April 2015}}</ref> However, a month earlier, ''Cosmopolitan''{{'}}s associate editor stated that they \"put forward the nomination myself\", indicating that the magazine {{ndash}} not the public {{ndash}} had been instrumental in promoting Gibson's award.<ref name=\"honest\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/health-lifestyle/lifestyle/2015/3/an-honest-account-of-our-experience-with-belle-gibson/|title=An honest account of our experience with Belle Gibson|last1=Sams|first1=Lauren|date=17 March 2015|work=Cosmopolitan Australia|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518091405/http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/health-lifestyle/lifestyle/2015/3/an-honest-account-of-our-experience-with-belle-gibson/|archive-date=18 May 2015|publisher=Bauer Media Group}}</ref>\n\nA conventional cancer research professional from the [[Garvan Institute of Medical Research]] also went public to state that, by failing to conduct basic [[fact checking]] and providing \"unfiltered [[public relations|PR]]\" to Gibson's untested claims, an uncritical media had been complicit in her \"scam\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burke|first1=Liz|title='They are all complicit': Cancer researcher Dr Darren Saunders slams Belle Gibson's 'enablers'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/they-are-all-complicit-cancer-researcher-dr-darren-saunders-slams-belle-gibsons-enablers/story-fneuzlbd-1227317296471|accessdate=23 April 2015|agency=News.com.au|publisher=News Limited}}</ref>\n\n===Erasing the story===\nOnce the controversy surfaced in the media, ''The Whole Pantry'' began removing any comments made on its (since deleted) Facebook page that questioned Gibson's claims, asserting that these comments only added to \"the misinformation\" of the initial Fairfax article. This selective deletion drew even more negative comment.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryall|first1=Jenni|title=The mystery of Belle Gibson, who claimed she cured cancer with clean living|url=http://mashable.com/2015/03/29/belle-gibson-whole-pantry/|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Mashable Australia|publisher=Mashable Inc.}}</ref>\n\nSimultaneously, posts that Gibson had made on her Instagram account that made reference to her cancers or charitable donations were also selectively deleted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Does Belle Gibson Actually Have Cancer?|url=http://realitybasedmedicine.blogspot.com.au/2015/03/does-belle-gibson-actually-have-cancer.html|website=Reality Based Medicine|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref> Soon after, all posts were deleted from Gibson's and ''The Whole Pantry'''s Instagram accounts. Around the same time, individual postings about Gibson's cancer, and claims of having died briefly while under heart surgery, were also being selectively deleted by the administrator of her blog \"at the request of a user\".<ref name=\"erased\">{{cite news|last1=Guilliatt|first1=Richard|title=Whole Pantry founder Belle Gibson's stories of beating terminal cancer erased from internet|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/whole-pantry-founder-belle-gibsons-stories-of-beating-terminal-cancer-erased-from-internet/story-fni0fit3-1227257742137|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref> Accounts across a number of social media platforms were soon either abandoned, made private, or deleted in their entirety.<ref name=\"fiction\"/>{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nGibson subsequently established another Facebook account under the alias Harry Gibson, which was made private and used to hit back at Facebook followers questioning her claims or speaking to the media.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cavanagh|first1=Rebekah|last2=Tuohy|first2=Wendy|title=Belle Gibson slams 'fake cancer' claims in online rant|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/digital-life-news/health-blogger-and-app-developer-belle-gibson-hits-back-at-bullying-critics-20150315-144g0v.html|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp}}</ref>\n\n===Admission of deceit===\nIn late April 2015, Gibson gave an interview to ''The Australian Women's Weekly'', in which she admitted to having fabricated all her cancer claims. Gibson attributed her deceit to her upbringing, and specifically to [[child neglect|neglect]] by her now-[[Family estrangement|estranged]] mother, claiming to having been forced to take care of herself and her brother since the age of 5.<ref name=\"news.com.au\">{{cite news|last1=Sullivan|first1=Rebecca|title=Belle Gibson: 'No, None of it is true'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-no-none-of-it-is-true/story-fniym874-1227315232565|accessdate=22 April 2015|work=news.com.au|agency=News Limited}}</ref> The interview was, however, described as an admission of deceit, without expression of regret or apology.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Matt|title=Nothing to like about this pretty little liar|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/nothing-to-like-about-this-pretty-little-liar/story-fni0ffsx-1227320920457|accessdate=30 April 2015|work=Herald Sun|publisher=NewsCorp Ltd|date=25 April 2015}}</ref> In a May 2015 interview with the same magazine, Gibson's mother Natalie Dal-Bello refuted several claims Gibson had made about her family, including the false claim that her brother was [[autism|autistic]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson's mum slams troubled childhood claims as 'a lot of rubbish'|url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibsons-mum-slams-troubled-childhood-claims-as-a-lot-of-rubbish/story-fneuz9ev-1227358455303|accessdate=18 May 2015|work=news.com.au|agency=News Limited}}</ref> Gibson's ''Women's Weekly'' interview was arranged by [[Bespoke Approach]], and Gibson was provided ''[[pro bono]]'' representation by the company during the interview.<ref name=\"news.com.au\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/strewth/toil-for-the-belle/news-story/5be985d1f1b73c1a0fda7dab453ffab1|title=Toil for the Belle|last1=Jeffrey|first1=James|date=23 April 2015|work=The Australian|accessdate=25 April 2015|url-status=live|publisher=NewsCorp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Gibson was rumoured to have received A$45,000 for an interview with [[Nine Network]]'s ''[[60 Minutes (Australian TV program)|60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/belle-gibson-promises-to-tell-the-whole-truth-i-have-lost-everything/news-story/dd6e5b8b3a31d7f13b7805214332e5a5|title=Belle Gibson promises to tell the whole truth: \u2018I have lost everything\u2019|last=Willis|first=Charlotte|date=2015-06-25|website=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Corp Australia|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003193353/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/belle-gibson-promises-to-tell-the-whole-truth-i-have-lost-everything/news-story/dd6e5b8b3a31d7f13b7805214332e5a5|archive-date=2017-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/broadcast/nine-network-faces-backlash-over-60-minutes-interview-with-belle-gibson/news-story/311065149cfe5289ea2b4d3af6ef283d|title=Nine Network faces backlash over 60 Minutes interview with Belle Gibson|last=Guilliatt|first=Richard|date=25 Jun 2015|work=The Australian|publisher=News Corp|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-date=|access-date=24 Jun 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Legal action===\n\nConsumer Affairs Victoria brought legal action against Gibson for allegedly breaking Australian consumer law. The regulator said it had conducted an in-depth investigation of Gibson's activities and applied to Australia's Federal Court for leave to pursue legal action. Gibson's publisher, Penguin Australia, has already agreed to pay A$30,000 (US$22,200; \u00a315,300) to the Victorian Consumer Law Fund as a penalty for releasing The Whole Pantry, which was not fact checked.<ref name=\"ConsumerAffairs2016\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson: Australian blogger who faked cancer faces legal action|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-36195825|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2017, Federal Court Justice [[Debra Mortimer]] delivered the decision that \"most but not all\" of the claims were proven. Gibson did not appear in court for the decision. Justice Mortimer found that Gibson's claims had been misleading and deceptive, and that \"Ms. Gibson had no reasonable basis to believe she had cancer from the time she began making these claims in public to promote ''The Whole Pantry Book'' and the apps in mid-2013\", but there was not enough evidence to prove that she was not acting out of delusion.<ref name=\"judgement\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.9news.com.au/national/2017/03/15/06/22/belle-gibsons-judgement-to-be-handed-down-in-court|title=Disgraced wellness blogger Belle Gibson facing more than $1 million in fines|date=15 March 2017|work=9 News|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref><ref name=\"2017 FCA 240\">{{cite AustLII|FCA|240|2017|litigants=Director of Consumer Affairs Victoria v Gibson |date=15 March 2017 |courtname=[[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]]}}.</ref><ref name=\"fad\"/>\n\nIn September 2017, Gibson was fined A$410,000 (US$310,000; \u00a3240,000) for making false claims about her donations to charity.<ref name=\"2017 FCA 1148\">{{cite AustLII|FCA|1148|2017|litigants=Director of Consumer Affairs Victoria v Gibson (No 3) |date=28 September 2017 |courtname=[[Federal Court of Australia|Federal Court]]}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Karen |last=Percy |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-28/disgraced-wellness-blogger-belle-gibson-fined/8995500 |title=Fake wellness blogger Belle Gibson fined over cancer claims |date=28 September 2017 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Commission}}</ref> {{As of|2019|04}}, Gibson had not yet paid the fine, and authorities were seeking power to charge her with [[contempt of court]]. A new trial was set for 14 May  and she faced an undetermined number of years in jail if she did not attend.<ref>{{cite news |title=Belle Gibson faces jail time if $410k fine for cancer fraud goes unpaid |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-27/belle-gibson-faces-jail-term-for-unpaid-cancer-fraud-fine/10558150 |date=28 November 2018 |access-date=28 November 2018 |last=Oaten |first=James |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Belle Gibson to explain why she hasn\u2019t paid $410k fine for duping sick Aussies|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/belle-gibson-to-explain-why-she-hasnt-paid-410k-fine-for-duping-sick-aussies/news-story/43c24e05cb91d5b6f74f3aa2e26b392c|date=17 April 2019|access-date=18 April 2019|publisher=news.com.au}}</ref> As of mid-September 2019, Gibson still had not paid, claiming to be broke, and Consumer Affairs Victoria were still seeking to enforce the penalty.<ref>\"Belle Gibson 'in hiding'\". The Daily Telegraph (Australia), 15 Sep 2019, p. 11</ref> In a 2017 letter later released by the Federal Court, Gibson had stated that she was $170,000 in debt, and had $5,000 to her name.<ref name=\"letter\" />\n\n==House raid by police==\nOn 22 January 2020, the Sheriff\u2019s Office of Victoria  raided Gibson's home in Northcote and seized items to recoup Gibson's unpaid fines,<ref name=\"raided\"/> which, due to interest and costs, exceeded half a million dollars.<ref name=\"sheriff\"/>\n\n==Claimed adoption into Oromo community==\nOn 23 January 2020, a Shabo Media video from October 2019 surfaced in which Gibson was wearing a headscarf and speaking partially in [[Oromo language]] (referring to herself as \"Sanbotu\"), discussing the political situation in [[Ethiopia]] with an interviewer and referring to Ethiopia as \"back home\". She professed to have been adopted by the Ethiopian community in Melbourne after volunteering for four years, calling the adoption a gift from \"Allah\".<ref name=\"adopted\"/><ref name=\"community\"/>\n\nHowever, on the same day, the president of the Australian Oromo Community Association in Victoria, Tarekegn Chimdi, stated that Gibson was not a registered volunteer, \"is not a community member and she\u2019s also not working with the community,\" and that he had only seen her at events two or three times. He expressed that nobody seemed to know who she was and he had only just learnt of her backstory, and expressed a desire for her to stop saying she is part of the community.<ref name=\"rejected\"/><ref name=\"Melbourne\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ashley Kirilow]], a Canadian fraudster who raised money for cancer charities by falsely claiming that she had cancer\n*[[Michael Guglielmucci]], an Australian singer who claimed to have cancer to boost his performing career\n*[[Diet and cancer]]\n*[[Munchausen syndrome]] <ref name=\"sickness\"/><ref name=\"munchausen\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"fiction\">{{cite news|last1=Debelle|first1=Penelope|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-and-the-whole-pantry-is-her-story-fact-or-fiction/story-fni0dguy-1227265261138|title=Belle Gibson and The Whole Pantry: Is her story fact or fiction?|date=2015-03-16|work=The Advertiser|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419125643/https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/lifestyle/health/belle-gibson-and-the-whole-pantry-is-her-story-fact-or-fiction/news-story/e2470157576603c9d0f1743b6e238ebd|archive-date=2020-04-19|publisher=News Corp|last2=Hadfield|first2=Shelley|location=Adelaide, SA}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"letter\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/finance/money/wealth/2017-letter-belle-gibson-wrote-detailing-debts-released/news-story/1a9eb9b29b181fda21340c873a92cf0e|title=2017 letter Belle Gibson wrote detailing debts released|date=2020-02-18|work=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Pty Ltd|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301050632/https://www.news.com.au/finance/money/wealth/2017-letter-belle-gibson-wrote-detailing-debts-released/news-story/1a9eb9b29b181fda21340c873a92cf0e|archive-date=2020-03-01}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"munchausen\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/munchausen-syndrome-why-bloggers-like-cancer-fraud-belle-gibson-fake-sickness-online-10215185.html|title=Munchausen syndrome: Why bloggers like cancer fraud Belle Gibson fake sickness online|last=Nianias|first=Helen|date=2015-04-30|work=The Independent|publisher=Independent Digital News & Media Ltd|location=UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428224900/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/munchausen-syndrome-why-bloggers-like-cancer-fraud-belle-gibson-fake-sickness-online-10215185.html|archive-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Melbourne\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/belle-gibson-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community-in-melbourne/news-story/faef622ee9d2b5bee4e4a9518420c315|title=Belle Gibson has been adopted by Ethiopian community in Melbourne|last=Smith|first=Rohan|date=2020-01-24|work=News.Com.Au|publisher=News Pty Ltd|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126195951/https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/news-life/belle-gibson-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community-in-melbourne/news-story/faef622ee9d2b5bee4e4a9518420c315|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"fad\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/belle-gibson-backs-new-health-fad-ahead-of-court-judgment/news-story/d5850eb9a6c9c4c3e4420141c2a42f6a|title=Belle Gibson backs new health fad ahead of court judgment|last=Cavanagh|first=Rebekah|date=15 March 2017|work=Herald Sun|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-125528/https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/belle-gibson-backs-new-health-fad-ahead-of-court-judgment/news-story/d5850eb9a6c9c4c3e4420141c2a42f6a|archive-date=2020-02-01|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"community\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/belle-gibson-says-she-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/11895252|title=Belle Gibson 'adopted' by Ethiopian community|last=Kinsella|first=Elise|date=2020-01-23|work=ABC News|location=Australia|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126203125/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/belle-gibson-says-she-has-been-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/11895252|archive-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/business/apple-exposed-over-belle-gibson-affair-20171119-gzoasp.html|title=Apple exposed over Belle Gibson affair|last1=Toscano|first1=Nick|date=19 November 2017|work=The Age|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200124-223125/https://www.theage.com.au/business/apple-exposed-over-belle-gibson-affair-20171119-gzoasp.html|archive-date=2020-01-24|publisher=Fairfax|last2=Donelly|first2=Beau|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"The Australian\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/mega-blogger-belle-gibson-casts-doubt-on-her-own-cancer-claims/story-e6frg8zx-1227255933051|title=Mega-blogger Belle Gibson casts doubt on her own cancer claims|last1=Guilliatt|first1=Richard|date=10 March 2015|newspaper=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/2017.01.26-011131/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/megablogger-belle-gibson-casts-doubt-on-her-own-cancer-claims/news-story/de179f2f17de51d1071096eb7bd2bdee|archive-date=2017-01-26|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rejected\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibson-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/news-story/7947e2e0c3ef96814e3d1352605b61e2|title=Cancer fraudster rejected by Ethiopians|last=Akerman|first=Tessa|date=24 January 2020|work=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-132450/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibson-adopted-by-ethiopian-community/news-story/7947e2e0c3ef96814e3d1352605b61e2|archive-date=2020-02-01|publisher=News Corp Australia|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"adopted\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/people-entertainment/2020/01/23/belle-gibson-ethiopian-oromo/|title=Cancer fraudster Belle Gibson \u2018adopted\u2019 by Ethiopian community|date=January 23, 2020|work=The New Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123132020/https://thenewdaily.com.au/entertainment/people-entertainment/2020/01/23/belle-gibson-ethiopian-oromo/|archive-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"sheriff\">{{Cite news|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/people/2020/01/22/belle-gibson-cancer-sheriff-fine/|title=Sheriff raids cancer fraudster Belle Gibson's home over unpaid fine|last=AAP|date=2020-01-22|work=The New Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200122215711/https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/people/2020/01/22/belle-gibson-cancer-sheriff-fine/|archive-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"raided\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibsons-home-raided-by-sheriff-over-cancer-fraud/news-story/5d016d637d8f73a0756afe77d301920c|title=Belle Gibson\u2019s home raided by sheriff over cancer fraud fine|last=Urban|first=Rebecca|date=2020-01-22|work=The Australian|url-status=dead|archive-url=http://archive.today/20200201-210004/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/belle-gibsons-home-raided-by-sheriff-over-cancer-fraud/news-story/5d016d637d8f73a0756afe77d301920c|archive-date=2020-02-01|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150314032024/http://thewholepantryapp.com/ The Whole Pantry website], registered by Gibson\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Belle}}\n[[Category:Australian fraudsters]]\n[[Category:Health fraud]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:People from Launceston, Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Pseudoscientific diet advocates]]\n[[Category:Alternative cancer treatment advocates]]\n[[Category:Confidence tricksters]]\n[[Category:Medical controversies in Australia]]\n[[Category:People convicted for health fraud]]\n", "name_user": "CatCafe", "label": "safe", "comment": "m", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belle_Gibson"}
{"title_page": "Orange Line (MBTA)", "text_new": "{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Orange Line\n|color       = {{rcr|MBTA|Orange}}\n|image       = Inbound train passing Wellington Yard tower, July 2019.JPG\n|image_width = 320px\n|caption     = An inbound train passing the Wellington Yard signal tower\n|type        = [[Rapid transit]]\n|system      = [[MBTA subway]]\n|status      = Operational\n|locale      = [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|start       = {{bts|Oak Grove}}\n|end         = {{bts|Forest Hills}}\n|stations    = 20\n|routes      = \n|daily_ridership = 201,000 (2019)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/fmcb-meeting-docs/2019/05-may/2019-05-20/2019-05-20-fmcb-joint-22-ridership-fy18-q3.pdf |title=Quarterly Ridership Update: Third Quarter FY19 |date=May 20, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |page=6}}</ref>\n|open        = 1901\n|close       = \n|owner       = [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|MBTA]]\n|operator    = MBTA\n|character   = \n|stock       = [[Hawker Siddeley Canada|Hawker Siddeley]] #12 Main Line cars<br />[[CRRC]] #14 Orange Line cars\n|linelength  = {{convert|11|mi|km}}\n|tracklength = \n|tracks = \n|gauge       = {{Track gauge|ussg}}\n|electrification = [[Third rail]]\n|speed       = \n|elevation   = \n|map         = {{MBTA Orange Line}}\n|box_width   = auto\n}}\n\nThe '''Orange Line''' is one of the [[MBTA subway|four subway lines]] of the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]].  It extends from {{bts|Forest Hills}} in [[Jamaica Plain, Massachusetts|Jamaica Plain]], [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]] in the south to {{bts|Oak Grove}} in [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] in the north.  It meets the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]] at {{bts|Downtown Crossing}}, the [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]] at {{bts|State}}, and the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]] at {{bts|Haymarket}} and [[North Station]].  It connects with [[Amtrak]] service at {{bts|Back Bay}} and North Station, and with [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] service at Back Bay, North Station, Forest Hills, {{bts|Ruggles}} station in [[Roxbury, Massachusetts|Roxbury]], and {{bts|Malden Center}} in Malden.  From 1901 to 1987, it provided the first elevated rapid transit in Boston; the [[Washington Street Elevated|last elevated section]] was torn down in 1987 when the southern portion of the line was moved to the [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]].\n\nAll stations on the Orange Line are [[handicapped accessible]]. These stations are equipped with high-level platforms for easy boarding, as well as elevators for easy platform access.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of the MBTA}}\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:Charlestown El on Charlestown Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|220px|The Charlestown El running over the Charlestown Bridge]]\nThe Main Line of the electric [[Boston Elevated Railway]] opened in segments, starting in 1901. It proceeded from [[Sullivan Square]] along the [[Charlestown Elevated]] to the [[Canal Street Incline]] near [[North Station]]. It was carried underground by the [[Tremont Street Subway]] (now part of the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]]), returning above ground at the [[Pleasant Street Incline]] (now closed, located just south of [[Boylston station]]). A temporary link connected from there to the [[Washington Street Elevated]], which in 1901 ran from this point via Washington Street to Dudley Square (which is most of what is now Phase 1 of the [[Silver Line (MBTA)|Silver Line]]).\n\nAlso in 1901, the [[Atlantic Avenue Elevated]] opened, branching at Causeway Street to provide an alternate route through downtown Boston (along the shoreline, where today there is no rail transit) to the Washington Street Elevated.\n\nIn 1908, a new '''Washington Street Tunnel''' opened, allowing Main Line service to travel from the [[Charlestown Elevated]], underground via an additional new portal at the [[Canal Street Incline]], under downtown Boston and back up again to meet the Washington Street Elevated and Atlantic Avenue Elevated near [[Chinatown, Boston|Chinatown]]. The stations wee richly decorated with tile work, mosaics, and copper; after criticism of the large [[Tremont Street Subway]] headhouses, most entrances were comparatively modest and set into buildings.<ref name=newboston>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Es9AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA307 |title=Rapid Transit and Civic Beauty |magazine=New Boston |date=November 1910 |volume=1 |issue=7 |pages=307\u2013314 |first=Frederick W. |last=Coburn |via=Google Books}}</ref> Use of the parallel Tremont Street Subway was returned exclusively to [[streetcar]]s.\n\nBy 1909, the Washington Street Elevated had been extended south to {{bts|Forest Hills}}. Trains from Washington Street were routed through the new subway, either all the way to Sullivan Square, or back around in a loop via the subway and then the Atlantic Avenue Elevated.\n\nIn 1919, the same year that the Atlantic Avenue Elevated was partially damaged in Boston's [[Great Molasses Flood]], the Charlestown Elevated was extended north from Sullivan Square to [[Everett, Massachusetts|Everett]], over surface right-of-way parallel to [[Massachusetts Route 99|Alford Street/Broadway]], with a [[Movable bridge|drawbridge]] over the [[Mystic River]].<ref name=netransit /> The Boston Elevated had long-term plans to continue this extension further north to [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]], a goal which would only be achieved decades later, under [[MBTA|public ownership]] and not via the Everett route.\n\n===Closure of Atlantic Avenue Elevated and ownership changes===\n[[File:Rowes Wharf Station (13083218675).jpg|thumb|left|Rowes Wharf station on the Atlantic Avenue Elevated in 1942 \u2013 four years after closure \u2013 just before being demolished]]\nFollowing a 1928 accident at a tight curve on Beach Street, the southern portion of the [[Atlantic Avenue Elevated]], between South Station and Tower D on Washington Street, was closed (except for rush-hour trips from Dudley to North Station via the Elevated), breaking the loop; non-rush-hour Atlantic Avenue service was reduced to a shuttle between North and South Stations.<ref name=\"netransit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/MBTARouteHistory.pdf|title=Changes to Transit Service in the MBTA district|last=Belcher|first=Jonathan|date=27 June 2015|format=PDF|publisher=NETransit|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>  In 1938, the remainder of the Atlantic Avenue Elevated was closed, leaving the subway as the only route through downtown \u2013 what is now the Orange Line between {{bts|Haymarket}} and {{bts|Chinatown}} stations.\n\nOwnership of the railway was transferred from the private Boston Elevated Railway to the public Metropolitan Transit Authority (MTA) in 1947; the MTA was itself reconstituted as the modern [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] (MBTA) in 1964.\n\n===Orange Line naming===\n[[File:Tile mosaic at Boylston Street station, October 1914.jpg|thumb|left|Station sign at Boylston Street (now Chinatown) station in 1914. In 1967, the station was renamed Essex to avoid confusion with the preexisting [[Boylston station|Green Line station]] a block away.]]\nThe line was known as the '''Main Line Elevated''' under the [[Boston Elevated Railway]], and the '''Forest Hills\u2013Everett Elevated''' (Route 2 on maps) under the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority (Boston)|Metropolitan Transportation Authority]].\n\nAfter taking over operations in August 1964, the MBTA began rebranding many elements of Boston's public transportation network. Colors were assigned to the rail lines on August 26, 1965 as part of a wider modernization developed by [[Cambridge Seven Associates]]. [[Peter Chermayeff]] assigned [[Red Line (MBTA)|red]], [[Green Line (MBTA)|green]], and [[Blue Line (MBTA)|blue]] to the other three lines based on geographic features; however, according to Chermayeff, the Main Line El \"ended up being orange for no particular reason beyond color balance.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.citylab.com/design/2018/09/how-boston-got-its-t/570004/ |title=How Boston Got Its \u2018T\u2019 |magazine=[[CityLab (web magazine)|CityLab]] |quote=I remember sitting in my Cambridge office preparing for a meeting with the MBTA in which I would be proposing colored lines. I had markers in front of me and I chose red for the line that went to Harvard since it\u2019s a well-known institution whose main color is crimson. One line went up the North Shore of Boston up to the coastal areas, so it seemed obvious to call that the Blue Line. The line that serves Olmsted\u2019s Emerald Necklace was an obvious choice for green. And then the fourth line ended up being orange for no particular reason beyond color balance. |date=September 17, 2018 |first=Mark |last=Byrnes}}</ref> The firm originally planned for yellow instead of orange, but yellow was rejected after testing because yellow text was difficult to read on a white background.<ref name=111th>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721150920/http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/downtown/gallery/orange_line_111th_anniversary?pg=11 |archivedate=July 21, 2017 |url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/downtown/gallery/orange_line_111th_anniversary?pg=11 |title=MBTA Orange Line's 111th anniversary |last=Ba Tran |first=Andrew |date=June 2012 |newspaper=Boston Globe |quote=The Everett-Forest Hills Main Line Elevated was renamed the Orange Line on Aug. 25, 1965. The name comes from a section of Washington Street between Essex and Dover streets that had the name Orange Street until the early 19th century, said Clarke. However, according to architecture firm Cambridge Seven Associates, the Orange Line's color was a design choice after the yellow color option did not test well.}}</ref> (Yellow was later used for [[MBTA Bus]] service). The MBTA and transit historians later claimed that orange came from Orange Street, an early name for what is now part of Washington Street.<ref name=chronicle>{{cite book |url=http://web.mit.edu/cron/project/uncertainty/Dowd_Data/Baum_Snow/boston-history.txt |title=A Chronicle of the Boston Transit System |year=1992 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=MIT |last=Sanborn |first=George M.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Smart_Forms/News,_Events_and_Press_Releases/Curiosity_Carcard-opt9a-FINAL.pdf |title=Curiosity Carcards |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |year=2012}}</ref><ref name=111th />\n\nIn January and February 1967, the four original Washington Street Tunnel stations were renamed. Transfer stations were given the same name for all lines: Winter and Summer stations plus Washington on the Red Line became Washington, Milk and State plus Devonshire on the Blue Line became {{bts|State Street}} after the cross street, and Union and Friend plus Haymarket Square on the Green Line became {{bts|Haymarket}} after [[Haymarket Square (Boston)|Haymarket Square]].<ref name=netransit /> Boylston Street was renamed Essex to avoid confusion with nearby [[Boylston station]] on the Green Line.<ref name=netransit />\n\nIn May 1987, Essex was renamed {{bts|Chinatown}} after the adjacent [[Chinatown, Boston|Chinatown neighborhood]], and Washington renamed {{bts|Downtown Crossing}} after the [[Downtown Crossing|adjacent shopping district]].<ref name=netransit /> In March 2010, New England Medical Center station was renamed as {{bts|Tufts Medical Center}} two years after [[Tufts Medical Center|the eponymous hospital]] changed its name.<ref name=netransit />\n\n===Rerouting of Charlestown and Everett service===\n[[Image:Main Line Elevated.jpg|thumb|Map of the original Main Line Elevated and related lines]]\nThe [[Boston Transportation Planning Review]] looked at the line in the 1970s, considering extensions to reach the [[Massachusetts Route 128|Route 128]] [[beltway]], with termini at [[Reading, Massachusetts|Reading]] in the north and [[Dedham, Massachusetts|Dedham]] in the south. As a result of this review, the [[Charlestown Elevated]] \u2013 which served the [[Charlestown, Boston, Massachusetts|Charlestown]] neighborhood north of downtown Boston and the inner suburb of [[Everett, Massachusetts|Everett]] \u2013 was demolished and replaced in 1975.\n\nThe '''Haymarket North Extension''' rerouted the Orange Line through an [[Haymarket North Extension|underwater crossing]] of the [[Charles River]]. Service in Charlestown was replaced with service along [[Boston and Maine]] tracks routed partially beneath an elevated section of [[Interstate 93]], ultimately to {{bts|Wellington}} and then to {{bts|Oak Grove}} in [[Malden, Massachusetts]] instead of Everett. Rail service to Everett was replaced with buses.\n\n===Closure of Washington Street Elevated===\n[[File:ELEVATED RAILROAD STRUCTURE AND BLIGHTED AREA BELOW WASHINGTON STREET SOUTH FROM THE CORNER OF BARTLETT - NARA - 550012.tif|thumb|left|View under Washington Street Elevated, looking south from Bartlett Street (1973)]]\nConstruction of [[Interstate 95 in Massachusetts|Interstate 95]] into downtown Boston was cancelled in 1972 after [[Freeway revolt|local protest]] over the necessary demolition. However, land for I-95's [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]] through [[Roxbury, Massachusetts|Roxbury]] had already been cleared of buildings; moreover, the state had already committed to using this vacant land for transportation purposes.<ref name=bosrds>{{cite web|last=Anderson|first=Steve|title=Southwest Expressway (I-95, unbuilt)|url=http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/southwest/|work=bostonroads.com|accessdate=3 August 2013}}</ref> As a result, instead of an 8-lane Interstate highway with a relocated Orange Line running in its median (in a manner similar to the [[Chicago Transit Authority]]'s [[Dan Ryan branch|Dan Ryan]], [[Blue Line (CTA)|Congress, and O'Hare branches]]), the space would be occupied by the realigned Orange Line, a reconstructed three-track mainline for [[Amtrak]]'s [[Northeast Corridor]] and [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] trains, and [[Southwest Corridor Park|a linear park]].  After this re-routing was accomplished in 1987, the Washington Street Elevated was torn down, the last major segment of the original elevated line to be demolished.\n\n[[File:South Bay Tunnel junction HDR.JPG|thumb|right|The modern view from the platform at {{bts|Chinatown}} shows the remains of the Washington Street Tunnel that led to the Elevated in the distance. In the foreground, the tracks curve rightward into the [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]].]]\nBetween April 30 and May 3, 1987, the [[Washington Street Elevated]] south of the [[Chinatown station (MBTA)|Chinatown station]] was closed to allow the Orange Line to be tied into the new Southwest Corridor. On May 4, 1987, the Orange Line was rerouted from the southern end of the Washington Street Tunnel onto the new Southwest Corridor. Instead of rising up to elevated tracks, it now veered west at the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] and followed the Pike and the old [[Boston and Albany Railroad]] right-of-way to the existing [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] stop at {{bts|Back Bay}}. It then continued along new tracks, partially covered and partially open but depressed, to {{bts|Forest Hills}}. This MBTA right-of-way is also shared by [[Amtrak]] as part of the national [[Northeast Corridor]] intercity passenger rail service.\n{{external media | width = 210px | float = right | video1 = [http://bostonlocaltv.org/catalog/V_K8BUH3FQFLF84AV Orange Line El Stations], 11:42, 4/30/1987, Boston TV Digital News<ref name=\"BTVDN\">{{cite web | title =Orange Line El Stations | work =Boston TV Digital News | publisher =[[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]] | date = April 30, 1987| url =http://bostonlocaltv.org/catalog/V_K8BUH3FQFLF84AV | accessdate =September 15, 2016 }}</ref> }}\n\nWhile ending more or less at the same terminus (Forest Hills), the new routing passes significantly to the west of its previous route on Washington Street; local residents were promised replacement service. Originally, plans provided for [[light rail vehicle]]s [[street running]] in mixed traffic, from Washington Street to Dudley Square, then diverting southeastward on Warren Street towards Dorchester. In 2002, Phase 1 of the [[Silver Line (MBTA)|Silver Line]] [[bus rapid transit]] was added to connect Washington Street to the downtown subways, attempting to address this service need. This replacement service was controversial, as many residents preferred the return of rail transportation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/files/documents/2018/03/02/RDMreport.pdf|title=Roxbury-Dorchester-Mattapan Transit Needs Study|date=September 2012|page=53 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Station renovations===\nIn the mid-1980s, the MBTA spent $80 million to extend the platforms of seven Red Line and three Orange Line stations ({{bts|Essex}}, [[Downtown Crossing station|Washington]], and {{bts|State}}) to allow the use of six-car trains.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/annualreportmas1985mass_0 |title=1985 Annual Report |year=1985 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |page=[https://archive.org/details/annualreportmas1985mass_0/page/13 13] |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Washington and Essex were made fully accessible, as was the northbound platform at Essex. The Southwest Corridor station opened in 1987 were all fully [[accessible]]. Six-car trains entered service on August 18, 1987.<ref name=netransit /> {{bts|Oak Grove}} was also renovated around 1987.<ref name=2007doc>{{cite web |url=https://old.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/Accessibility/final%20report%20082407%20on%20CD.pdf |title=Evaluation of MBTA Paratransit and Accessible Fixed Route Transit Services: Final Report |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=Tran Systems and Planners Collaborative |date=August 24, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThis left only {{bts|Haymarket}}, five stations on the Haymarket North Extension, and the southbound platform at Chinatown inaccessible by the 1990 passage of the [[Americans with Disabilities Act]].<ref name=bluebook1990>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/ridershipservice990mass |edition=3 |title=Ridership and Service Statistics |date=November 1990 |pages=1\u20134 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=Operations Directorate Planning Division |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Construction at {{bts|Sullivan Square}} and {{bts|Wellington}} began in 1991.<ref name=chronicle /> {{bts|Haymarket}} was retrofitted with elevators in 2000.<ref name=2007doc /> The 1975-built {{bts|North Station}} was expanded into a \"superstation\" with a cross-platform transfer to the Green Line; elevators were in installed in 2001, though the Green Line did not use the station until 2004.<ref name=2007doc /><ref name=netransit /> The southbound platform at Chinatown was made accessible in 2002.<ref name=atthet>{{cite web |url=https://old.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/documents/Accessibility_at_the_T.pdf |title=Accessibility Projects at the MBTA |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=March 2005}}</ref><ref name=2007doc /> Renovations to {{bts|Community College}} and {{bts|Malden Center}} were completed in 2005, making the Orange Line the first of the four original [[MBTA subway]] lines to become fully accessible.<ref name=atthet />\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Assembly===\n[[File:Trains at Assembly station from north headhouse, September 2014.JPG|thumb|right|Assembly station on its first day of service in September 2014]]\n{{main|Assembly station}}\nIn the early 2000s, [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]] began planning an [[infill]] station between {{bts|Sullivan}} and {{bts|Wellington}} to serve the new [[Assembly Square]] development. The $57 million station was funded by the state's Executive Office of Housing and Economic Development, FTA Section 5309 New Starts program, and Federal Realty Investment Trust (the developer of Assembly Square).<ref name=globe>{{cite news |title=MBTA board OK\u2019s millions for stations |url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-10-06/news/30253264_1_blue-line-orange-line-red-line |newspaper=Boston Globe |author=Moskowitz, Eric |date=6 October 2011 |accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref> Construction began in late 2011 and finished in mid 2014.<ref name=tuftsdaily>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuftsdaily.com/news/construction-on-assembly-square-t-stop-to-begin-later-this-fall-1.2659745#.T9gJtLWvKSq |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204172940/http://www.tuftsdaily.com/news/construction-on-assembly-square-t-stop-to-begin-later-this-fall-1.2659745 |archivedate=4 December 2011 |title=Construction on Assembly Square T stop to begin later this fall |newspaper=Tufts Daily |author=Coughlin, Kerri |date=25 October 2011 |accessdate=13 June 2012}}</ref> The new station, {{bts|Assembly}}, opened on September 2, 2014.<ref name=sept2>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2014/08/27/somerville-new-assembly-square-mbta-station-open-next-week/SgjW9ub8Oil5uDXXbeK5OO/story.html |title=Somerville\u2019s New Assembly Square MBTA Station to Open Next Week |newspaper=Boston Globe |author=Hofherr, Justine |date=27 August 2014 |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> It was the first new station on the MBTA subway system since 1987.<ref name=sept2 />\n\n===Winter issues and resiliency work===\nDuring the [[2014\u201315 North American winter#Northeastern United States|unusually brutal winter of 2014\u20132015]], the entire MBTA system was shut down on several occasions by heavy snowfalls. The aboveground sections of the Orange and Red lines were particularly vulnerable due to their exposed third rail, which iced over during storms. When a single train stopped due to power loss, other trains soon stopped as well; without continually running trains pushing snow off the rails, the lines were quickly covered in snow. (Because the Blue Line was built with overhead lines on its surface section due to its proximity to corrosive salt air, it was not subject to icing issues.)\n\nStarting in 2015, the MBTA began implementing its $83.7 million Winter Resiliency Program, much of which focused on preventing similar issues with the Orange and Red lines. The [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]] section of the Orange Line is located in a trench and is protected from the worst weather, but the 1970s-built [[Haymarket North Extension]] had older infrastructure and was in worse shape. From {{bts|Sullivan Square}} north, it is exposed to the weather and largely built on an embankment, rendering it more vulnerable. That section is receiving new heated third rail, switch heaters, and snow fences to reduce the impacts of inclement weather.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/business/news/2015/09/23/how-the-mbta-getting-winter-ready/SeTjLsOSUUZ1nGlIAc5p3N/story.html |title=Winter is coming, and the MBTA is getting ready |newspaper=Boston Globe |last=Vaccaro |first=Adam |date=23 September 2015 |accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=6442454500&month=&year |title=Gov. Baker Announces $83.7 Million MBTA Winter Resiliency Plan |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=4 June 2015}}</ref> The work requires [[bustitution]] of the line from Sullivan Square to Oak Grove on certain weeknights and weekends.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=6442454945&month=&year= |title=Winter Resiliency Work Continues on the Red Line: WEEKEND TRAIN SERVICE BETWEEN JFK/UMASS AND QUINCY CENTER SUSPENDED |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Authority|first1=Massachusetts Bay Transportation|title=Weekend Orange Line Service Suspended between Sullivan and North Stations < News < MBTA - Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2386|website=www.mbta.com|accessdate=3 November 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, the MBTA awarded a $218 million signal contract for the Red and Orange Lines, which will allow 4.5-minute headways on the Orange Line beginning in 2022.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://blog.mass.gov/transportation/mbta/mbta-awards-signal-upgrade-contract-for-red-and-orange-lines/ |title=MBTA Awards Signal Upgrade Contract for Red and Orange Lines |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |date=October 2, 2018 |first=Klark |last=Jessen}}</ref>\n\n===Historical routes===\n{{collapse top|title=Route diagram templates of the various Orange Line routes over its history}}\n{| style=\"border:1px solid darkgrey;background:#f9f9f9\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|width=300|'''1901\u20131908'''\n|width=300|'''1908\u20131938'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|{{MBTA Orange Line 1901-1908}}\n|{{MBTA Orange Line 1908-1938}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|width=300|'''1938\u20131975'''\n|width=300|'''1975\u20131987'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|width=300|{{MBTA Orange Line 1938-1975}}\n|width=300|{{MBTA Orange Line 1975-1987}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|'''1987\u2013present'''\n|'''Notes'''\n|- style=\"text-align:justify;\"\n|width=300|{{MBTA Orange Line 1987-present}}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n*Haymarket and State got their modern names in 1967. Downtown Crossing and Chinatown also changed names in 1967, but changed again in 1987.\n*New England Medical Center was renamed Tufts Medical Center in 2010.\n|}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n==Station listing==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Location\n!Station\n!Opened\n!Notes and connections\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Oak Grove}}\n|March 20, 1977\n|{{bus icon}} [[MBTA Bus]]: {{MBTABus|131}}, {{MBTABus|132}}, {{MBTABus|136}}, {{MBTABus|137}}\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Malden Center}}\n|December 27, 1975\n|{{rint|boston|rail}} [[MBTA Commuter Rail]]: [[Haverhill Line]]<br />{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|97}}, {{MBTABus|99}}, {{MBTABus|101}}, {{MBTABus|104}}, {{MBTABus|105}}, {{MBTABus|106}}, {{MBTABus|108}}, {{MBTABus|131}}, {{MBTABus|132}}, {{MBTABus|136}}, {{MBTABus|137}}, {{MBTABus|411}}, {{MBTABus|430}}\n|-\n|[[Medford, Massachusetts|Medford]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Wellington}}\n|September 6, 1975\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|97}}, {{MBTABus|99}}, {{MBTABus|100}}, {{MBTABus|106}}, {{MBTABus|108}}, {{MBTABus|110}}, {{MBTABus|112}}, {{MBTABus|134}}, {{MBTABus|710}}\n|-\n|[[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Assembly}}\n|September 2, 2014\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Charlestown, Boston]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Sullivan Square}}\n|rowspan=3|April 7, 1975\n|Original elevated station was open from June 10, 1901 to April 4, 1975<br />{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|86}}, {{MBTABus|89}}, {{MBTABus|90}}, {{MBTABus|91}}, {{MBTABus|92}}, {{MBTABus|93}}, {{MBTABus|95}}, {{MBTABus|101}}, {{MBTABus|104}}, {{MBTABus|105}}, {{MBTABus|109}}, {{MBTABus|194}}, {{MBTABus|CT2}}\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Community College}}\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[North End, Boston]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} [[North Station]]\n|Original elevated station was open from June 10, 1901 to April 4, 1975<br />{{rint|subway}} [[MBTA subway]]: [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]]<br/>{{bus icon}} [[MBTA Bus]]: {{MBTABus|4}}<br/>{{rint|Boston|rail}} [[MBTA Commuter Rail]]: [[Fitchburg Line]], [[Lowell Line]], [[Haverhill Line]], and [[Newburyport/Rockport Line]]<br/>{{rint|us|Amtrak}} [[Amtrak]]: {{lnl|Amtrak|Downeaster}}\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Haymarket}}\n|rowspan=4|November 30, 1908\n|{{rint|subway}} MBTA subway: Green Line<br />{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}, {{MBTABus|92}}, {{MBTABus|93}}, {{MBTABus|111}}, {{MBTABus|191}}, {{MBTABus|192}}, {{MBTABus|193}}, {{MBTABus|194}}, {{MBTABus|325}}, {{MBTABus|326}}, {{MBTABus|352}}, {{MBTABus|354}}, {{MBTABus|426}}, {{MBTABus|428}}, {{MBTABus|434}}, {{MBTABus|450}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Downtown Boston]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|State}}\n|{{rint|subway}} MBTA subway: [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]]<br />{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|4}}, {{MBTABus|92}}, {{MBTABus|93}}, {{MBTABus|191}}, {{MBTABus|192}}, {{MBTABus|193}}, {{MBTABus|352}}, {{MBTABus|354}}\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Downtown Crossing}}\n|{{rint|subway}} [[MBTA subway]]: [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]]<br />{{bus icon|12px}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|SL5}}, {{MBTABus|7}}, {{MBTABus|11}}, {{MBTABus|501}}, {{MBTABus|504}}, {{MBTABus|505}}, {{MBTABus|553}}, {{MBTABus|554}}, {{MBTABus|556}}, {{MBTABus|558}}<br />At {{bts|Park Street}}: {{rint|subway}} Green Line; {{bus icon}} {{MBTABus|43}}, {{MBTABus|55}}, {{MBTABus|191}}, {{MBTABus|192}}, {{MBTABus|193}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Chinatown, Boston]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Chinatown}}\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|SL4}}, {{MBTABus|SL5}}, {{MBTABus|11}}, {{MBTABus|191}}\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Tufts Medical Center}}\n|rowspan=9|May 4, 1987\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|SL4}}, {{MBTABus|SL5}}, {{MBTABus|11}}, {{MBTABus|43}}, {{MBTABus|191}}\n|-\n|[[Back Bay, Boston]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Back Bay}}\n|{{rint|Boston|rail}} MBTA Commuter Rail: [[Providence/Stoughton Line]], [[Framingham/Worcester Line]], [[Franklin Line]] and [[Needham Line]]<br />{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|10}}, {{MBTABus|39}}, {{MBTABus|170}}<br />{{rint|us|Amtrak}} Amtrak: {{lnl|Amtrak|Acela Express}}, {{lnl|Amtrak|Northeast Regional}}, and {{lnl|Amtrak|Lake Shore Limited}}\n|-\n|[[South End, Boston]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Massachusetts Avenue}}\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|1}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Roxbury, Boston]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Ruggles}}\n|{{rint|boston|rail}} MBTA Commuter Rail: Providence/Stoughton Line, Franklin Line, and Needham Line<br />{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|8}}, {{MBTABus|15}}, {{MBTABus|19}}, {{MBTABus|22}}, {{MBTABus|23}}, {{MBTABus|28}}, {{MBTABus|42}}, {{MBTABus|43}}, {{MBTABus|44}}, {{MBTABus|45}}, {{MBTABus|47}}, {{MBTABus|CT2}}, {{MBTABus|CT3}}\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Roxbury Crossing}}\n|{{bus icon|12px}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|15}}, {{MBTABus|22}}, {{MBTABus|23}}, {{MBTABus|29}}, {{MBTABus|44}}, {{MBTABus|45}}, {{MBTABus|66}}, {{MBTABus|MIS}}\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Jackson Square}}\n|{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|14}}, {{MBTABus|22}}, {{MBTABus|29}}, {{MBTABus|41}}, {{MBTABus|44}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Jamaica Plain, Boston]]\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Stony Brook}}\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Green Street}}\n|\n|-\n|bgcolor=ffdfdf|{{access icon}} {{bts|Forest Hills}}\n|Original elevated station was open from November 22, 1909 to April 30, 1987<br />{{rint|boston|rail}} MBTA Commuter Rail: Needham Line<br/>{{bus icon}} MBTA Bus: {{MBTABus|16}}, {{MBTABus|21}}, {{MBTABus|30}}, {{MBTABus|31}}, {{MBTABus|32}}, {{MBTABus|34}}, {{MBTABus|34E}}, {{MBTABus|35}}, {{MBTABus|36}}, {{MBTABus|37}}, {{MBTABus|38}}, {{MBTABus|39}}, {{MBTABus|40}}, {{MBTABus|42}}, {{MBTABus|50}}, {{MBTABus|51}}, {{MBTABus|192}} \n|}\n\n==Rolling stock==\n[[File:Inbound Orange Line train at Assembly station, 2 September 2014.JPG|thumb|left|#12 Main Line car at Assembly station]]\n[[File:Orange line (MBTA) Interior.jpg|thumb|right|Interior of a #12 Main Line car]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" |\n|-\n! Series #\n! Year Built\n! Manufacturer\n! Car<br />Length\n! Car<br />Width\n! Photo\n! Fleet numbers<br /><small>(Total ordered)</small>\n! Amount active<br><small>(as of February 22, 2020)</small>\n|-bo,\n! #12<br>Main Line\n| 1979\u20131981\n| [[Hawker Siddeley Canada]]\n| {{convert|65|ft|m|sigfig=2|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|9|ft|3|in|m|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Orange Line train enters Ruggles.jpg|100px]]\n|\n* 1200\u20131319<br /><small>(120 total)</small>\n| align=center | 114\n|-\n! #14<br>Orange\n| 2018\u20132022\n| [[CRRC]]\n| {{convert|65|ft|m|sigfig=2|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|9|ft|3|in|m|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:New Orange Line Train Exterior 06.jpg|100px]]\n|\n* 1400\u20131551<br /><small>(152 total)</small>\n| align=center | 14<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/03/new-orange-line-trains-removed-from-service |title=New Orange Line cars pulled from service due to 'a fault with the bolsters' |last=MacNeill |first=Arianna |date=March 3, 2020 |website=[[Boston.com]] |access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\nThe \"T\" previously had a fleet of [[Pullman-Standard]] heavy rail cars for the Orange Line. These cars, known as 01100s, had been in service since the 1950s, and saw service on both the elevated and the northern extension before they were retired in 1981. Several remained on the property for some time before being scrapped. The 01100 cars were a favorite for fans, as the small motorman's cab enabled passengers to stand at the front for an operator's-eye view.\n\nThe Orange Line is [[standard gauge]] [[heavy rail]] and uses a [[third rail]] for power. The current fleet was built between 1979 and 1981 by [[Hawker Siddeley Canada]] (now [[Alstom]]) of [[Thunder Bay]], [[Ontario]], Canada. They are 65 feet (20 m) long and 9&nbsp;ft 3&nbsp;in (2.8 m) wide, with three pairs of doors on each side. They are based on the PA3 model used by [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson|PATH]] in [[New Jersey]] and the R44/R46/R62/R68 models used by the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] in [[New York City]] There are 120 cars, numbered 01200-01319. All in-service Orange Line trains run in six-car consists.\n\n===New CRRC trains===\n[[File:New Orange Line cars at Wellington Yard (2), August 2018.JPG|thumb|left|The first set of the new rolling stock during testing in 2018]]\n\nIn late 2008, the MBTA began the planning process for new Orange and Red Line vehicles. The agency originally planned for a simultaneous order for 146 Orange Line cars (to replace the whole fleet) and 74 Red Line cars (to replace the older 1500 and 1600 series cars). A similar order was used in the late 1970s for the current Orange Line cars and the old Blue Line cars, ordered at the same time and largely identical except for size and color.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctps.org/data/pdf/studies/transit/pmt/PMT_Ch5.pdf |title=CHAPTER 5: Priorities for Achieving a State of Good Repair |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=December 2009 |page=5-2 |work=The Program for Mass Transportation |author=Central Transportation Planning Staff}}</ref> In October 2013, MassDOT announced plans for a $1.3 billion subway car order for the Orange and Red Lines, which would provide 152 new Orange Line cars to replace the existing 120-car fleet and add more frequent service.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=27773&month=&year= |title=Governor Patrick Announces Major Transportation Funding Investments |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=22 October 2013 |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2014, the MassDOT Board awarded a $566.6 million contract to a [[China]] based manufacturer [[China CNR Corporation|CNR]] (which became part of [[CRRC Corporation|CRRC]] the following year) to build 152 replacement railcars for the Orange Line, as well as additional cars for the Red Line.<ref name=\"chinese\"/> The other bidders were [[Bombardier Transportation]], [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries]] and [[Hyundai Rotem]].  CNR began building the cars at a new manufacturing plant in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]], with initial deliveries expected in 2018 and all cars in service by 2023.<ref name=\"chinese\"/> The Board forwent federal funding to allow the contract to specify the cars be built in Massachusetts, to create a local railcar manufacturing industry.<ref>[https://www.masslive.com/business/2019/12/mbta-orange-line-problems-not-linked-to-springfield-built-cars.html MBTA: Orange Line problems not linked to Springfield-built cars]</ref> In conjunction with the new rolling stock, the remainder of the $1.3 billion allocated for the project would pay for testing, signal improvements and expanded maintenance facilities, as well as other related expenses.<ref name=\"chinese\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wbur.org/2014/10/22/chinese-company-mbta-contract | title=Chinese Company Hopes MBTA Contract Will Be U.S. Launching Pad | publisher=WMUR.com | date=October 22, 2014 | accessdate=October 23, 2014 | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TWhYgTHz | archivedate=October 22, 2014}}</ref> Sixty percent of the car's components are sourced from the United States.<ref>{{cite news|title=MBTA Orange Line Cars Pulled From Service: Report|first=William C. |last=Vantuono|date=October 1, 2019|publisher=Railway Age|url=https://www.railwayage.com/passenger/rapid-transit/mbta-orange-line-cars-pulled-from-service-report/}}</ref>\n\nAfter delays due to issues with the train's control system, the first new train entered revenue service on August 14, 2019;<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2019-08-14/first-new-mbta-orange-line-cars-enter-passenger-service |title=First New MBTA Orange Line Cars Enter Passenger Service |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=August 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2019/03/25/orange-line-cars-delayed-again |title=MBTA Orange Line Car Rollout Delayed Until Summer |newspaper=WBUR |date=March 25, 2019 |first=Laney |last=Ruckstuhl}}</ref> Replacement of the signal system is expected to be complete by 2022 on the Orange Line; the total cost is $218 million for both the Red and Orange Lines.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/10/01/signal-problem-mbta-takes-aim-prime-cause-delays-with-new-signal-system/LcrvW47h5jCAZZBNe9oFcO/story.html |title=Signal problem? MBTA takes aim at prime cause of delays with new signal system |first=Adam |last=Vaccaro |date=October 1, 2018 |newspaper=Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nWhile waiting for new cars, service has deteriorated due to maintenance problems with the old cars. The number of trains at rush hour was reduced from 17 (102 cars) to 16 (96 cars) in 2011; in the same year, daily ridership surpassed 200,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/06/08/not-your-imagination-your-orange-line-commute-more-crowded-than-used/yywGoxRfnaIjU52IGwBnLP/story.html |title=Your Orange Line commute is more crowded than it used to be. |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=8 June 2016 |first=Nicole |last=Dungca |accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref> Increased running times \u2013 largely due to longer dwell times from increased ridership \u2013 resulted in headways being lengthened from 5 minutes before 2011 to 6 minutes in 2016. The increased fleet size with the new trains will allow headways to be reduced to between 4 and 5 minutes at peak.<ref name=state>{{cite web |url=http://www.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/About_the_T/Board_Meetings/StateoftheOrangeLine61616.pdf |title=MBTA State of the Service: Orange Line Heavy Rail |page=26 |date=6 June 2016 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority}}</ref> In the interim, a 2016 test of platform markings at North Station - which show boarding passengers where to stand to avoid blocking alighting passengers - resulted in a one-third decrease in dwell times.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2016/06/06/orange-line-loading-times-stickers |title=Why Orange Line trains are leaving North Station a little bit faster now |newspaper=Boston Globe |date=6 June 2016 |first=Adam |last=Vaccaro |accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe new cars have faced several issues since their August entry into service. In November 2019, a car derailed while undergoing initial testing at the Wellington yard. The last car of a six car trainset had jumped the rails while going over a [[Railroad switch|switch]], however no major damage had been reported. Several months earlier, the first two trainsets were taken out of service due to safety issues following the inadvertent opening of a passenger door while the train was in motion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/11/18/new-orange-line-train-becomes-latest-mbta-derailment/ |title=New Orange Line train becomes latest MBTA derailment |newspaper=The Boston Herald |date=November 18, 2019 |first=Sean Philip |last=Cotter |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> Cars were also rechecked in early December 2019, after issues with sounds combined with passenger overload necessitated removal from service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/new-orange-line-trains-pulled-from-service-over-uncommon-noise-1575488557/30123555|title=MBTA finds cause of Orange Line's trains' 'uncommon noise'|date=2019-12-04|website=WCVB|language=en|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/12/03/t-pulls-new-orange-line-trains-from-service-for-uncommon-noise/|title=T pulls new Orange Line trains from service for \u2018uncommon noise\u2019|date=2019-12-03|website=Boston Herald|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> The first train was restored to service in January 2020.<ref>{{cite news|title=One new Orange Line train back on tracks as T says problems are fixed|first=John R.|last= Ellement|first2=Adam|last2= Vaccaro|date=January 7, 2020|publisher=The Boston Globe|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/01/07/metro/one-new-orange-line-train-back-tracks-t-promises-problems-are-fixed/}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Facilities===\n[[File:Orange Line trains in Wellington Carhouse, October 2014.JPG|thumb|right|Orange Line trains in Wellington Carhouse, the Orange Line's heavy maintenance facility, in 2014]]\n\nThe Orange Line has two tracks for most of its length; a third track is present between Wellington station and the Charles River portal.<ref name=\"nycsubway\" /> This track is used to bypass construction on the other two, and for testing newly delivered cars for the Orange Line. The primary maintenance and storage facility is at Wellington station.<ref name=\"nycsubway\">{{cite web|url=http://world.nycsubway.org/us/boston/orange.html |title=MBTA Orange Line |work=world.nycsubway.org |date= |accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> Had the Orange Line been extended to [[Reading, Massachusetts|Reading]], the third track would have been the northbound local track and the present-day northbound track would likely have become a bi-directional express track.\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|MBTA Orange Line}}\n{{Attached KML}}\n*[http://www.mbta.com/schedules_and_maps/subway/lines/?route=ORANGE Official MBTA Orange Line information]\n*[http://world.nycsubway.org/us/boston/main_line_el.html Historic American Engineering Record (HAER) documentation of Boston Elevated Railway Company's Main Line Elevated (Former Orange Line)]\n*[http://world.nycsubway.org/us/boston/orange.html Orange Line] from nycsubway.org \u2013 Includes detailed description and photos of current Orange Line\n*[http://www.jphs.org/transportation/orange-line-memories.html Jamaica Plain Historical Society \u2013 Orange Line Memories]\n*[http://www.jphs.org/transportation/orange-line-replaced-old-railroad-embankment.html Jamaica Plain Historical Society \u2013 Orange Line Replaced Old Railroad Embankment]\n*[http://www.cityofboston.gov/news/default.aspx?id=5823 \"An Elevated View: The Orange Line\"], Boston Public Library exhibit about Orange Line elevated line history, October 2012 \u2013 January 2013 ([http://www.bpl.org/news/calendar_ex.htm?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D102013346 BPL description])\n\n{{MBTA}}\n{{USSubway}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orange Line (Mbta)}}\n[[Category:Orange Line (MBTA)| ]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1901]]\n[[Category:1901 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in the United States]]\n[[Category:600 V DC railway electrification]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Orange Line\n|color       = {{rcr|MBTA|Orange}}\n|image       = Inbound train passing Wellington Yard tower, July 2019.JPG\n|image_width = 320px\n|caption     = An inbound train passing the Wellington Yard signal tower\n|type        = [[Rapid transit]]\n|system      = [[MBTA subway]]\n|status      = Operational\n|locale      = [[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|start       = {{bts|Oak Grove}}\n|end         = {{bts|Forest Hills}}\n|stations    = 20\n|routes      = \n|daily_ridership = 201,000 (2019)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/sites/default/files/fmcb-meeting-docs/2019/05-may/2019-05-20/2019-05-20-fmcb-joint-22-ridership-fy18-q3.pdf |title=Quarterly Ridership Update: Third Quarter FY19 |date=May 20, 2019 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |page=6}}</ref>\n|open        = 1901\n|close       = \n|owner       = [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|MBTA]]\n|operator    = MBTA\n|character   = \n|stock       = [[Hawker Siddeley Canada|Hawker Siddeley]] #12 Main Line cars<br />[[CRRC]] #14 Orange Line cars\n|linelength  = {{convert|11|mi|km}}\n|tracklength = \n|tracks = \n|gauge       = {{Track gauge|ussg}}\n|electrification = [[Third rail]]\n|speed       = \n|elevation   = \n|map         = {{MBTA Orange Line}}\n|box_width   = auto\n}}\n\nThe '''Orange Line''' is one of the [[MBTA Subway|four subway lines]] of the [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]].  It extends from {{bts|Forest Hills}} in [[Jamaica Plain, Massachusetts|Jamaica Plain]], [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]] in the south to {{bts|Oak Grove}} in [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] in the north.  It meets the [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red Line]] at {{bts|Downtown Crossing}}, the [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]] at {{bts|State}}, and the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]] at {{bts|Haymarket}} and [[North Station]].  It connects with [[Amtrak]] service at {{bts|Back Bay}} and North Station, and with [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] service at Back Bay, North Station, Forest Hills, {{bts|Ruggles}} station in [[Roxbury, Massachusetts|Roxbury]], and {{bts|Malden Center}} in Malden.  From 1901 to 1987, it provided the first elevated rapid transit in Boston; the [[Washington Street Elevated|last elevated section]] was torn down in 1987 when the southern portion of the line was moved to the [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]].\n\nAll stations on the Orange Line are [[handicapped accessible]]. These stations are equipped with high-level platforms for easy boarding, as well as elevators for easy platform access.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of the MBTA}}\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:Charlestown El on Charlestown Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|220px|The Charlestown El running over the Charlestown Bridge]]\nThe Main Line of the electric [[Boston Elevated Railway]] opened in segments, starting in 1901. It proceeded from [[Sullivan Square]] along the [[Charlestown Elevated]] to the [[Canal Street Incline]] near [[North Station]]. It was carried underground by the [[Tremont Street Subway]] (now part of the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]]), returning above ground at the [[Pleasant Street Incline]] (now closed, located just south of [[Boylston station]]). A temporary link connected from there to the [[Washington Street Elevated]], which in 1901 ran from this point via Washington Street to Dudley Square (which is most of what is now Phase 1 of the [[Silver Line (MBTA)|Silver Line]]).\n\nAlso in 1901, the [[Atlantic Avenue Elevated]] opened, branching at Causeway Street to provide an alternate route through downtown Boston (along the shoreline, where today there is no rail transit) to the Washington Street Elevated.\n\nIn 1908, a new '''Washington Street Tunnel''' opened, allowing Main Line service to travel from the [[Charlestown Elevated]], underground via an additional new portal at the [[Canal Street Incline]], under downtown Boston and back up again to meet the Washington Street Elevated and Atlantic Avenue Elevated near [[Chinatown, Boston|Chinatown]]. The stations wee richly decorated with tile work, mosaics, and copper; after criticism of the large [[Tremont Street Subway]] headhouses, most entrances were comparatively modest and set into buildings.<ref name=newboston>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3Es9AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA307 |title=Rapid Transit and Civic Beauty |magazine=New Boston |date=November 1910 |volume=1 |issue=7 |pages=307\u2013314 |first=Frederick W. |last=Coburn |via=Google Books}}</ref> Use of the parallel Tremont Street Subway was returned exclusively to [[streetcar]]s.\n\nBy 1909, the Washington Street Elevated had been extended south to {{bts|Forest Hills}}. Trains from Washington Street were routed through the new subway, either all the way to Sullivan Square, or back around in a loop via the subway and then the Atlantic Avenue Elevated.\n\nIn 1919, the same year that the Atlantic Avenue Elevated was partially damaged in Boston's [[Great Molasses Flood]], the Charlestown Elevated was extended north from Sullivan Square to [[Everett, Massachusetts|Everett]], over surface right-of-way parallel to [[Massachusetts Route 99|Alford Street/Broadway]], with a [[Movable bridge|drawbridge]] over the [[Mystic River]].<ref name=netransit /> The Boston Elevated had long-term plans to continue this extension further north to [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]], a goal which would only be achieved decades later, under [[MBTA|public ownership]] and not via the Everett route.\n\n===Closure of Atlantic Avenue Elevated and ownership changes===\n[[File:Rowes Wharf Station (13083218675).jpg|thumb|left|Rowes Wharf station on the Atlantic Avenue Elevated in 1942 \u2013 four years after closure \u2013 just before being demolished]]\nFollowing a 1928 accident at a tight curve on Beach Street, the southern portion of the [[Atlantic Avenue Elevated]], between South Station and Tower D on Washington Street, was closed (except for rush-hour trips from Dudley to North Station via the Elevated), breaking the loop; non-rush-hour Atlantic Avenue service was reduced to a shuttle between North and South Stations.<ref name=\"netransit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transithistory.org/roster/MBTARouteHistory.pdf|title=Changes to Transit Service in the MBTA district|last=Belcher|first=Jonathan|date=27 June 2015|format=PDF|publisher=NETransit|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>  In 1938, the remainder of the Atlantic Avenue Elevated was closed, leaving the subway as the only route through downtown \u2013 what is now the Orange Line between {{bts|Haymarket}} and {{bts|Chinatown}} stations.\n\nOwnership of the railway was transferred from the private Boston Elevated Railway to the public Metropolitan Transit Authority (MTA) in 1947; the MTA was itself reconstituted as the modern [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] (MBTA) in 1964.\n\n===Orange Line naming===\n[[File:Tile mosaic at Boylston Street station, October 1914.jpg|thumb|left|Station sign at Boylston Street (now Chinatown) station in 1914. In 1967, the station was renamed Essex to avoid confusion with the preexisting [[Boylston station|Green Line station]] a block away.]]\nThe line was known as the '''Main Line Elevated''' under the [[Boston Elevated Railway]], and the '''Forest Hills\u2013Everett Elevated''' (Route 2 on maps) under the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority (Boston)|Metropolitan Transportation Authority]].\n\nAfter taking over operations in August 1964, the MBTA began rebranding many elements of Boston's public transportation network. Colors were assigned to the rail lines on August 26, 1965 as part of a wider modernization developed by [[Cambridge Seven Associates]]. [[Peter Chermayeff]] assigned [[Red Line (MBTA)|red]], [[Green Line (MBTA)|green]], and [[Blue Line (MBTA)|blue]] to the other three lines based on geographic features; however, according to Chermayeff, the Main Line El \"ended up being orange for no particular reason beyond color balance.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.citylab.com/design/2018/09/how-boston-got-its-t/570004/ |title=How Boston Got Its \u2018T\u2019 |magazine=[[CityLab (web magazine)|CityLab]] |quote=I remember sitting in my Cambridge office preparing for a meeting with the MBTA in which I would be proposing colored lines. I had markers in front of me and I chose red for the line that went to Harvard since it\u2019s a well-known institution whose main color is crimson. One line went up the North Shore of Boston up to the coastal areas, so it seemed obvious to call that the Blue Line. The line that serves Olmsted\u2019s Emerald Necklace was an obvious choice for green. And then the fourth line ended up being orange for no particular reason beyond color balance. |date=September 17, 2018 |first=Mark |last=Byrnes}}</ref> The firm originally planned for yellow instead of orange, but yellow was rejected after testing because yellow text was difficult to read on a white background.<ref name=111th>{{cite news |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721150920/http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/downtown/gallery/orange_line_111th_anniversary?pg=11 |archivedate=July 21, 2017 |url=http://archive.boston.com/yourtown/boston/downtown/gallery/orange_line_111th_anniversary?pg=11 |title=MBTA Orange Line's 111th anniversary |last=Ba Tran |first=Andrew |date=June 2012 |newspaper=Boston Globe |quote=The Everett-Forest Hills Main Line Elevated was renamed the Orange Line on Aug. 25, 1965. The name comes from a section of Washington Street between Essex and Dover streets that had the name Orange Street until the early 19th century, said Clarke. However, according to architecture firm Cambridge Seven Associates, the Orange Line's color was a design choice after the yellow color option did not test well.}}</ref> (Yellow was later used for [[MBTA Bus]] service). The MBTA and transit historians later claimed that orange came from Orange Street, an early name for what is now part of Washington Street.<ref name=chronicle>{{cite book |url=http://web.mit.edu/cron/project/uncertainty/Dowd_Data/Baum_Snow/boston-history.txt |title=A Chronicle of the Boston Transit System |year=1992 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |via=MIT |last=Sanborn |first=George M.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://cdn.mbta.com/uploadedfiles/Smart_Forms/News,_Events_and_Press_Releases/Curiosity_Carcard-opt9a-FINAL.pdf |title=Curiosity Carcards |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |year=2012}}</ref><ref name=111th />\n\nIn January and February 1967, the four original Washington Street Tunnel stations were renamed. Transfer stations were given the same name for all lines: Winter and Summer stations plus Washington on the Red Line became Washington, Milk and State plus Devonshire on the Blue Line became {{bts|State Street}} after the cross street, and Union and Friend plus Haymarket Square on the Green Line became {{bts|Haymarket}} after [[Haymarket Square (Boston)|Haymarket Square]].<ref name=netransit /> Boylston Street was renamed Essex to avoid confusion with nearby [[Boylston station]] on the Green Line.<ref name=netransit />\n\nIn May 1987, Essex was renamed {{bts|Chinatown}} after the adjacent [[Chinatown, Boston|Chinatown neighborhood]], and Washington renamed {{bts|Downtown Crossing}} after the [[Downtown Crossing|adjacent shopping district]].<ref name=netransit /> In March 2010, New England Medical Center station was renamed as {{bts|Tufts Medical Center}} two years after [[Tufts Medical Center|the eponymous hospital]] changed its name.<ref name=netransit />\n\n===Rerouting of Charlestown and Everett service===\n[[Image:Main Line Elevated.jpg|thumb|Map of the original Main Line Elevated and related lines]]\nThe [[Boston Transportation Planning Review]] looked at the line in the 1970s, considering extensions to reach the [[Massachusetts Route 128|Route 128]] [[beltway]], with termini at [[Reading, Massachusetts|Reading]] in the north and [[Dedham, Massachusetts|Dedham]] in the south. As a result of this review, the [[Charlestown Elevated]] \u2013 which served the [[Charlestown, Boston, Massachusetts|Charlestown]] neighborhood north of downtown Boston and the inner suburb of [[Everett, Massachusetts|Everett]] \u2013 was demolished and replaced in 1975.\n\nThe '''Haymarket North Extension''' rerouted the Orange Line through an [[Haymarket North Extension|underwater crossing]] of the [[Charles River]]. Service in Charlestown was replaced with service along [[Boston and Maine]] tracks routed partially beneath an elevated section of [[Interstate 93]], ultimately to {{bts|Wellington}} and then to {{bts|Oak Grove}} in [[Malden, Massachusetts]] instead of Everett. Rail service to Everett was replaced with buses.\n\n===Closure of Washington Street Elevated===\n[[File:ELEVATED RAILROAD STRUCTURE AND BLIGHTED AREA BELOW WASHINGTON STREET SOUTH FROM THE CORNER OF BARTLETT - NARA - 550012.tif|thumb|left|View under Washington Street Elevated, looking south from Bartlett Street (1973)]]\nConstruction of [[Interstate 95 in Massachusetts|Interstate 95]] into downtown Boston was cancelled in 1972 after [[Freeway revolt|local protest]] over the necessary demolition. However, land for I-95's [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]] through [[Roxbury, Massachusetts|Roxbury]] had already been cleared of buildings; moreover, the state had already committed to using this vacant land for transportation purposes.<ref name=bosrds>{{cite web|last=Anderson|first=Steve|title=Southwest Expressway (I-95, unbuilt)|url=http://www.bostonroads.com/roads/southwest/|work=bostonroads.com|accessdate=3 August 2013}}</ref> As a result, instead of an 8-lane Interstate highway with a relocated Orange Line running in its median (in a manner similar to the [[Chicago Transit Authority]]'s [[Dan Ryan branch|Dan Ryan]], [[Blue Line (CTA)|Congress, and O'Hare branches]]), the space would be occupied by the realigned Orange Line, a reconstructed three-track mainline for [[Amtrak]]'s [[Northeast Corridor]] and [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] trains, and [[Southwest Corridor Park|a linear park]].  After this re-routing was accomplished in 1987, the Washington Street Elevated was torn down, the last major segment of the original elevated line to be demolished.\n\n[[File:South Bay Tunnel junction HDR.JPG|thumb|right|The modern view from the platform at {{bts|Chinatown}} shows the remains of the Washington Street Tunnel that led to the Elevated in the distance. In the foreground, the tracks curve rightward into the [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]].]]\nBetween April 30 and May 3, 1987, the [[Washington Street Elevated]] south of the [[Chinatown station (MBTA)|Chinatown station]] was closed to allow the Orange Line to be tied into the new Southwest Corridor. On May 4, 1987, the Orange Line was rerouted from the southern end of the Washington Street Tunnel onto the new Southwest Corridor. Instead of rising up to elevated tracks, it now veered west at the [[Massachusetts Turnpike]] and followed the Pike and the old [[Boston and Albany Railroad]] right-of-way to the existing [[MBTA Commuter Rail]] stop at {{bts|Back Bay}}. It then continued along new tracks, partially covered and partially open but depressed, to {{bts|Forest Hills}}. This MBTA right-of-way is also shared by [[Amtrak]] as part of the national [[Northeast Corridor]] intercity passenger rail service.\n{{external media | width = 210px | float = right | video1 = [http://bostonlocaltv.org/catalog/V_K8BUH3FQFLF84AV Orange Line El Stations], 11:42, 4/30/1987, Boston TV Digital News<ref name=\"BTVDN\">{{cite web | title =Orange Line El Stations | work =Boston TV Digital News | publisher =[[WGBH Educational Foundation|WGBH]] | date = April 30, 1987| url =http://bostonlocaltv.org/catalog/V_K8BUH3FQFLF84AV | accessdate =September 15, 2016 }}</ref> }}\n\nWhile ending more or less at the same terminus (Forest Hills), the new routing passes significantly to the west of its previous route on Washington Street; local residents were promised replacement service. Originally, plans provided for [[light rail vehicle]]s [[street running]] in mixed traffic, from Washington Street to Dudley Square, then diverting southeastward on Warren Street towards Dorchester. In 2002, Phase 1 of the [[Silver Line (MBTA)|Silver Line]] [[bus rapid transit]] was added to connect Washington Street to the downtown subways, attempting to address this service need. This replacement service was controversial, as many residents preferred the return of rail transportation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/files/documents/2018/03/02/RDMreport.pdf|title=Roxbury-Dorchester-Mattapan Transit Needs Study|date=September 2012|page=53 |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Station renovations===\nIn the mid-1980s, the MBTA spent $80 million to extend the platforms of seven Red Line and three Orange Line stations ({{bts|Essex}}, [[Downtown Crossing station|Washington]], and {{bts|State}}) to allow the use of six-car trains.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/annualreportmas1985mass_0 |title=1985 Annual Report |year=1985 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |page=[https://archive.org/details/annualreportmas1985mass_0/page/13 13] |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Washington and Essex were made fully accessible, as was the northbound platform at Essex. The Southwest Corridor station opened in 1987 were all fully [[accessible]]. Six-car trains entered service on August 18, 1987.<ref name=netransit /> {{bts|Oak Grove}} was also renovated around 1987.<ref name=2007doc>{{cite web |url=https://old.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/Accessibility/final%20report%20082407%20on%20CD.pdf |title=Evaluation of MBTA Paratransit and Accessible Fixed Route Transit Services: Final Report |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=Tran Systems and Planners Collaborative |date=August 24, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThis left only {{bts|Haymarket}}, five stations on the Haymarket North Extension, and the southbound platform at Chinatown inaccessible by the 1990 passage of the [[Americans with Disabilities Act]].<ref name=bluebook1990>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/ridershipservice990mass |edition=3 |title=Ridership and Service Statistics |date=November 1990 |pages=1\u20134 |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |author=Operations Directorate Planning Division |via=Internet Archive}}</ref> Construction at {{bts|Sullivan Square}} and {{bts|Wellington}} began in 1991.<ref name=chronicle /> {{bts|Haymarket}} was retrofitted with elevators in 2000.<ref name=2007doc /> The 1975-built {{bts|North Station}} was expanded into a \"superstation\" with a cross-platform transfer to the Green Line; elevators were in installed in 2001, though the Green Line did not use the station until 2004.<ref name=2007doc /><ref name=netransit /> The southbound platform at Chinatown was made accessible in 2002.<ref name=atthet>{{cite web |url=https://old.mbta.com/uploadedFiles/documents/Accessibility_at_the_T.pdf |title=Accessibility Projects at the MBTA |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=March 2005}}</ref><ref name=2007doc /> Renovations to {{bts|Community College}} and {{bts|Malden Center}} were completed in 2005, making the Orange Line the first of the four original [[MBTA subway]] lines to become fully accessible.<ref name=atthet />\n{{Clear}}\n\n===Assembly===\n[[File:Trains at Assembly station from north headhouse, September 2014.JPG|thumb|right|Assembly station on its first day of service in September 2014]]\n{{main|Assembly station}}\nIn the early 2000s, [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]] began planning an [[infill]] station between {{bts|Sullivan}} and {{bts|Wellington}} to serve the new [[Assembly Square]] development. The $57 million station was funded by the state's Executive Office of Housing and Economic Development, FTA Section 5309 New Starts program, and Federal Realty Investment Trust (the developer of Assembly Square).<ref name=globe>{{cite news |title=MBTA board OK\u2019s millions for stations |url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-10-06/news/30253264_1_blue-line-orange-line-red-line |newspaper=Boston Globe |author=Moskowitz, Eric |date=6 October 2011 |accessdate=7 October 2011}}</ref> Construction began in late 2011 and finished in mid 2014.<ref name=tuftsdaily>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuftsdaily.com/news/construction-on-assembly-square-t-stop-to-begin-later-this-fall-1.2659745#.T9gJtLWvKSq |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204172940/http://www.tuftsdaily.com/news/construction-on-assembly-square-t-stop-to-begin-later-this-fall-1.2659745 |archivedate=4 December 2011 |title=Construction on Assembly Square T stop to begin later this fall |newspaper=Tufts Daily |author=Coughlin, Kerri |date=25 October 2011 |accessdate=13 June 2012}}</ref> The new station, {{bts|Assembly}}, opened on September 2, 2014.<ref name=sept2>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2014/08/27/somerville-new-assembly-square-mbta-station-open-next-week/SgjW9ub8Oil5uDXXbeK5OO/story.html |title=Somerville\u2019s New Assembly Square MBTA Station to Open Next Week |newspaper=Boston Globe |author=Hofherr, Justine |date=27 August 2014 |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> It was the first new station on the MBTA subway system since 1987.<ref name=sept2 />\n\n===Winter issues and resiliency work===\nDuring the [[2014\u201315 North American winter#Northeastern United States|unusually brutal winter of 2014\u20132015]], the entire MBTA system was shut down on several occasions by heavy snowfalls. The aboveground sections of the Orange and Red lines were particularly vulnerable due to their exposed third rail, which iced over during storms. When a single train stopped due to power loss, other trains soon stopped as well; without continually running trains pushing snow off the rails, the lines were quickly covered in snow. (Because the Blue Line was built with overhead lines on its surface section due to its proximity to corrosive salt air, it was not subject to icing issues.)\n\nStarting in 2015, the MBTA began implementing its $83.7 million Winter Resiliency Program, much of which focused on preventing similar issues with the Orange and Red lines. The [[Southwest Corridor (Boston)|Southwest Corridor]] section of the Orange Line is located in a trench and is protected from the worst weather, but the 1970s-built [[Haymarket North Extension]] had older infrastructure and was in worse shape. From {{bts|Sullivan Square}} north, it is exposed to the weather and largely built on an embankment, rendering it more vulnerable. That section is receiving new heated third rail, switch heaters, and snow fences to reduce the impacts of inclement weather.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/business/news/2015/09/23/how-the-mbta-getting-winter-ready/SeTjLsOSUUZ1nGlIAc5p3N/story.html |title=Winter is coming, and the MBTA is getting ready |newspaper=Boston Globe |last=Vaccaro |first=Adam |date=23 September 2015 |accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=6442454500&month=&year |title=Gov. Baker Announces $83.7 Million MBTA Winter Resiliency Plan |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=4 June 2015}}</ref> The work requires [[bustitution]] of the line from Sullivan Square to Oak Grove on certain weeknights and weekends.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mbta.com/about_the_mbta/news_events/?id=6442454945&month=&year= |title=Winter Resiliency Work Continues on the Red Line: WEEKEND TRAIN SERVICE BETWEEN JFK/UMASS AND QUINCY CENTER SUSPENDED |publisher=Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority |date=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Authority|first1=Massachusetts Bay Transportation|title=Weekend Orange Line Service Suspended between Sullivan and North Stations < News < MBTA - Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority|url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2386|website=www.mbta.com|accessdate=3 November 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, the MBTA awarded a $218 million signal contract for the Red and Orange Lines, which will allow 4.5-minute headways on the Orange Line beginning in 2022.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://blog.mass.gov/transportation/mbta/mbta-awards-signal-upgrade-contract-for-red-and-orange-lines/ |title=MBTA Awards Signal Upgrade Contract for Red and Orange Lines |publisher=Massachusetts Department of Transportation |date=October 2, 2018 |first=Klark |last=Jessen}}</ref>\n\n===Historical routes===\n{{collapse top|title=Route diagram templates of the various Orange Line routes over its history}}\n{| style=\"border:1px solid darkgrey;background:#f9f9f9\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|width=300|'''1901\u20131908'''\n|width=300|'''1908\u20131938'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|{{MBTA Orange Line 1901-1908}}\n|{{MBTA Orange Line 1908-1938}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|width=300|'''1938\u20131975'''\n|width=300|'''1975\u20131987'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|width=300|{{MBTA Orange Line 1938-1975}}\n|width=300|{{MBTA Orange Line 1975-1987}}\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|'''1987\u2013present'''\n|'''Notes'''\n|- style=\"text-align:justify;\"\n|width=300|{{MBTA Orange Line 1987-present}}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n*Haymarket and State got their modern names in 1967. Downtown Crossing and Chinatown also changed names in 1967, but changed again in 1987.\n*New England Medical Center was renamed Tufts Medical Center in 2010.\n|}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n==Station listing==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Location\n!Station\n!Opened\n!Notes and 